\par \tab JANOV PELORAT WATCHED, FOR THE FIRST TIME IN HIS LIFE, AS THE bright star graduated into an orb after what Trevize had called a \ldblquote micro-Jump.\rdblquote  The fourth planetthe habitable one and their immediate destination, Sayshell\endash 
then grew in size and prominence more slowly\endash over a period of days.
\par \tab A map of the planet had been produced by the computer and was displayed on a portable screening device, which Pelorat held in his lap.
\par \tab Trevize\endash with the aplomb of someone who had, in his time, touched down upon several dozen worlds\endash said, \ldblquote Don\rquote 
t start watching too hard too soon, Janov. We have to go through the entry station first and that can be tedious.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat looked up. \ldblquote Surely that\rquote s just a formality.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It is. But it can still be tedious.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote But it\rquote s peacetime.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of course. That means we\rquote ll be passed through. First, though, there\rquote s a little matter of the ecological balance. Every planet has its own and they don\rquote 
t want it upset. So they make a natural point of checking the ship for undesirable organisms, or infections. It\rquote s a reasonable precaution.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote We don\rquote t have such things, it seems to me.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No, we don\rquote t and they\rquote ll find that out. Remember, too, that Sayshell is not a member of the Foundation Federation, so there\rquote s certain to be some leaning over backward to demonstrate their independence.\rdblquote 

\par \tab A small ship came out to inspect them and a Sayshellian Customs official boarded. Trevize was brisk, not having forgotten his military days.
\par \tab \ldblquote The Far Star, out of Terminus,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Ship\rquote s papers. Unarmed. Private vessel. My passport. There is one passenger. His passport. We are tourists.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The Customs official wore a garish uniform in which crimson was the dominating color. Cheeks and upper lip were smooth-shaven, but he wore a short beard parted in such a way that tufts thrust out to both sides of his chin. He said, \ldblquote 
Foundation ship?\rdblquote 
\par \tab He pronounced it \ldblquote Foundaysun sip,\rdblquote 
 but Trevize was careful neither to correct him nor to smile. There were as many varieties of dialects to Galactic Standard as there were planets, and you just spoke your own. As long as there was cross-comprehension, it didn\rquote t matter.
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes, sir,\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote Foundation ship. Privately owned.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Very nice. Your lading, if you please.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote My what?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Your lading. What are you carrying?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Ah, my cargo. Here is the itemized list. Personal property only. We are not here to trade. As I told you, we are simply tourists.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The Customs official looked about curiously. \ldblquote This is rather an elaborate vessel for tourists.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Not by Foundation standards,\rdblquote  said Trevize with a display of good humor. \ldblquote And I\rquote m well off and can afford this.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Are you suggesting that I might be richified?\rdblquote  The official looked at him briefly, then looked away.
\par \tab Trevize hesitated a moment in order to interpret the meaning of the word, then another moment to decide his course of action. He said, \ldblquote No, it is not my intention to bribe you. I have no reason to bribe you\endash and you don\rquote 
t look like the kind of person who could be bribed, if that were my intention. You can look over the ship, if you wish.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No need,\rdblquote  said the official, putting away his pocket recorder. \ldblquote You have already been examined fo
r specific contraband infection and have passed. The ship has been assigned a radio wavelength that will serve as an approach beam.\rdblquote 
\par \tab He left. The whole procedure had taken fifteen minutes.
\par \tab Pelorat said in a low voice. \ldblquote Could he have made trouble? Did he really expect a bribe?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize shrugged. \ldblquote Tipping the Customs man is as old as the Galaxy and I would have done it readily if he had made a second try for it. As it is\endash well, I presume he prefers not to take a chance with a Foundation ship, and a fancy on
e, at that. The old Mayor, bless her cross-grained hide, said the name of the Foundation would protect us wherever we went and she wasn\rquote t wrong. It could have taken a great deal longer.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why? He seemed to find out what he wanted to know.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes, but he was courteous enough to check us by remote radioscanning. If he had wished, he could have gone over the ship with a hand-machine and taken hours. He could have put us both in a field hospital and kept us days.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What? My dear fellow!\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Don\rquote t get excited. He didn\rquote t do it. I thought he might, but he didn\rquote t. Which means we\rquote re free to land. I\rquote d like to go down gravitically\endash which could take us fifteen minutes\endash but I don\rquote 
t know where the permitted landing sites might be and I don\rquote t want to cause trouble. That means we\rquote ll have to follow the radio beam\endash which will take hours\endash as we spiral down through the atmosphere.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat looked cheerful. \ldblquote But that\rquote s excellent, Golan. Will we be going slowly enough to watch the terrain?\rdblquote  He held up his portable viewscreen with the map spread out on it at low magnification.
\par \tab \ldblquote After a fashion. We\rquote d have to get beneath the cloud deck, and we\rquote ll be moving at a few kilometers per second. It won\rquote t be ballooning through the atmosphere, but you\rquote ll spot the planetography.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Excellent! Excellent!\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said thoughtfully, \ldblquote I\rquote m wondering, though, if we\rquote ll be on Sayshell Planet long enough to make it worth our while to adjust the ship\rquote s clock to local time.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It depends on what we plan to do, I suppose. What do you think we\rquote ll be doing, Golan?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Our job is to find Gaia and I don\rquote t know how long that will take.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote We can adjust our wrist-strips and leave the ship\rquote s clock as is.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Good enough,\rdblquote  said Trevize. He looked down at the planet spreading broadly beneath them. \ldblquote No use waiting any longer. I\rquote 
ll adjust the computer to our assigned radio beam and it can use the gravities to mimic conventional flight. So! Let\rquote s go down, Janov, and see what we can find.\rdblquote 
\par \tab He stared at the planet thoughtfully as the ship began to move on its smoothly adjusted gravitational potential-curve.
\par \tab Trevize had never been in the Sayshell Union, but he knew that over the last century it had been steadfastly unfriendly to the Foundation. He was surprised\endash and a little dismayed\endash they had gotten through Customs so quickly.
\par \tab It didn\rquote t seem reasonable.
