\par \tab The Customs official\rquote s name was Jogoroth Sobhaddartha and he had been serving on the station on and off for half his life.
\par \tab He didn\rquote t mind the life, for it gave him a chance\endash one month out of three\endash to view his books, to listen to his music, and to be away from his wife and growing son.
\par \tab Of course, during the last two years the current Head of Customs had been a Dreamer, which was irritating. There is no one so insufferable as a person who gives no other excuse for a peculiar action than saying he had been directed to it in a dream.

\par \tab Personally Sobhaddartha decided he believed none of it, though he was careful not to say so aloud, since most people on Sayshell rather disapproved of antipsychic doubts. To become known as a materialist might put his forthcoming pension at risk.

\par \tab He stroked the two tufts of hair at his chin, one with his right hand and the other with his left, cleared his throat rather loudly, and then, with inappropriate casualness, said, \ldblquote Was that the ship, Head?\rdblquote 
\par \tab The Head, who bore the equally Sayshellian name of Namarath Godhisavatta, was concerned with a matter involving some computer-born data and did not look up. \ldblquote What ship?\rdblquote  he said.
\par \tab \ldblquote The Far Star. The Foundation ship. The one I just sent past. The one that was holographed from every angle. Was that the one you dreamed of?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Godhisavatta looked up now. He was a small man, with eyes that were almost black and that were surrounded by fine wrinkles that had not been produced by any penchant for smiling. He said, \ldblquote Why do you ask?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Sobhaddartha straightened up and allowed his dark and luxuriant eyebrows to approach each other. \ldblquote They said they were tourists, but I\rquote ve never seen a ship like that before and my own opinion is they\rquote re Foundation agents.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab Godhisavatta sat back in his chair. \ldblquote See here, my man, try as I might I cannot recall asking for your opinion.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote But Head, I consider it my patriotic duty to point out that\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab Godhisavatta crossed his arms over his chest and stared hard at the underling, who (though much the more impressive in physical stature and bearing) allowed himself to droop and take on a somehow bedraggled appearance under the gaze of his superior.

\par \tab Godhisavatta said, \ldblquote My man, if you know what is good for you, you will do your job without comment\endash or I\rquote 
ll see to it that there will be no pension when you retire, which will be soon if I hear any more on a subject that does not concern you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab In a low voice, Sobhaddartha said, \ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote  Then, with a suspicious degree of subservience in his voice, he added, \ldblquote Is it within the range of my duties, sir, to report that a second ship is in range of our screens?
\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Consider it reported,\rdblquote  Godhisavatta said irritably, returning to his work.
\par \tab \ldblquote With,\rdblquote  said Sobhaddartha even more humbly, \ldblquote characteristics very similar to the one I just sent through.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Godhisavatta placed his hands on the desk and lifted himself to his feet. \ldblquote A second one?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Sobhaddartha smiled inwardly. That sanguinary person born of an irregular union (he was referring to the Head) had clearly not dreamed of two ships. He said, \ldblquote Apparently, sir! I will now return to my post and await orders and I hope, sir
\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Sobhaddartha could not resist, pension-risk notwithstanding. \ldblquote And I hope, sir, we didn\rquote t send the wrong one through.\rdblquote 
