\endash including broader desert areas, to judge by the rusty color of much of the continental expanse.
\par \tab There were no signs of anything living. It seemed a world of sterile desert, gray plain, of endless wrinkles that might have represented mountainous areas, and, of course, of ocean.
\par \tab \ldblquote It looks lifeless,\rdblquote  muttered Pelorat.
\par \tab \ldblquote You don\rquote t expect to see any life-signs at this height,\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote As we get lower, you\rquote ll see the land turn green in patches. Before that, in fact, you\rquote ll see the twinkling l
andscape on the nightside. Human beings have a penchant for lighting their worlds when darkness falls; I\rquote ve never heard of a world that\rquote s an exception to that rule. In other words, the first sign of life you\rquote 
ll see will not only be human but technological.\rdblquote 
