s contracting spiral. It would be the first foreign world upon which he would ever stand. This thought somehow filled him with foreboding, despite the fact that all the millions of inhabited planets in the Galaxy 
had been colonized by people who had not been born upon them.
\par \tab All but one, he thought with a shudder of trepidation/delight.
\par **
\par \tab The spaceport was not large by Foundation standards, but it was well kept. Trevize watched the Far Star moved into a berth and locked in place. They were given an elaborate coded receipt.
\par \tab Pelorat said in a low voice, \ldblquote Do we just leave it here?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize nodded and placed his hand on the other\rquote s shoulder in reassurance. \ldblquote Don\rquote t worry,\rdblquote  he said in an equally low voice.
\par \tab They stepped into the ground-car they had rented and Trevize plugged in the map of the city, whose towers he could see on the horizon.
\par \tab \ldblquote Sayshell City,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote the capital of the planet. City\endash planet\endash star\endash all named Sayshell.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I\rquote m worried about the ship,\rdblquote  insisted Pelorat.
\par \tab \ldblquote Nothing to worry about,\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote We\rquote ll be back tonight, because it will be our sleeping quarters if we have to stay here more than a few hours. You have to understand, too, that there\rquote 
s an interstellar code of spaceport ethics that\endash as far as I know\endash 
has never been broken, even in wartime. Spaceships that come in peace are inviolate. If that were not so, no one would be safe and trade would be impossible. Any world on which that code was broken would be boycotted by the space pilots of the 
Galaxy. I assure you, no world would risk that. Besides\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Besides?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well, besides, I\rquote ve arranged with the computer that anyone who doesn\rquote t look and sound like one of us will be killed if he\endash or she\endash tries to board the ship. I\rquote ve taken the liberty of expl
aining that to the Port Commander. I told him very politely that I would love to turn off that particular facility out of deference to the reputation that the Sayshell City Spaceport holds for absolute integrity and security\endash 
throughout the Galaxy, I said\endash but the ship is a new model and I didn\rquote t know how to turn it off.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote He didn\rquote t believe that, surely.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of course not! But he had to pretend he did, as otherwise he would have no choice but to be insulted. And since there would be nothing he could do about that, being insulted would only lead to humiliation. And since he didn\rquote 
t want that, the simplest path to follow was to believe what I said.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And that\rquote s another example of how people are?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes. You\rquote ll get used to this.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote How do you know this ground-car isn\rquote t bugged?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I thought it might be. So when they offered me one, I took another one at random. If they\rquote re all bugged\endash well, what have we been saying that\rquote s so terrible?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat looked unhappy. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know how to say this. It seems rather impolite to complain, but I don\rquote t like the way it smells. There\rquote s an\endash odor.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote In the ground-car?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well, in the spaceport, to begin with. I suppose that\rquote s the way spaceports smell, but the ground-car carries the odor with it. Could we open the windows?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize laughed. \ldblquote I suppose I could figure out which portion of the control panel will do that trick, but it won\rquote t help. This planet stinks. Is it very bad?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It\rquote s not very strong, but it\rquote s noticeable\endash and somewhat repulsive. Does the whole world smell this way?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I keep forgetting you\rquote ve never been on another world. Every inhabited world has its own odor. It\rquote s the 
general vegetation, mostly, though I suppose the animals and even the human beings contribute. And as far as I know, nobody ever likes the smell of any world when he first lands on it. But you\rquote 
ll get used to it, Janov. In a few hours, I promise you won\rquote t notice.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Surely you don\rquote t mean that all worlds smell like this.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No. As I said, each has its own. If we really paid attention or if our noses were a little keener\endash like those of Anacreonian dogs\endash we could probably tell which world we were on with one snif
f. When I first entered the Navy I could never eat the first day on a new world; then I learned the old spacer trick of sniffing a handkerchief with the world-scent on it during the landing. By the time you get out into the open world, you don\rquote 
t smell it. And after a while, you get hardened to the whole thing; you just learn to disregard it. \endash The worst of it is returning home, in fact.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Do you think Terminus doesn\rquote t smell?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Are you telling me it does?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of course it does. Once you get acclimated to the smell of another world, such as Sayshell, you\rquote 
ll be surprised at the stench of Terminus. In the old days, whenever the locks opened on Terminus after a sizable tour of duty, all the crew would call out, \lquote Back home to the crap.\rquote  \rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat looked revolted.
\par \tab The towers of the city were perceptibly closer, but Pelorat kept his eyes fixed on their immediate surroundings. There were other ground-cars moving in both directions and an occasional air-car above, but Pelorat was studying the trees.
\par \tab He said, \ldblquote The plant life seems strange. Do you suppose any of it is indigenous?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I doubt it,\rdblquote  said Trevize absently. He was studying the map and attempting to adjust the programming of the car\rquote s computer. \ldblquote There\rquote s not much in the way of indigenous life on any hu
man planet. Settlers always imported their own plants and animals\endash either at the time of settling or not too long afterward.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It seems strange, though.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You don\rquote t expect the same varieties from world to world, Janov.
\par \tab I was once told that the Encyclopedia Galactica people put out an atlas of varieties which ran to eighty-seven fat computer-discs and was incomplete even so\endash and outdated anyway, by the time it was finished.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The ground-car moved on and the outskirts of the city gaped and engulfed them. Pelorat shivered slightly, \ldblquote I don\rquote t think much of their city architecture.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote To each his own,\rdblquote  said Trevize with the indifference of the seasoned space traveler.
\par \tab \ldblquote Where are we going, by the way?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Trevize with a certain exasperation, \ldblquote I\rquote m trying to get the computer to guide this thing to the tourist center. I hope the computer knows the one-way streets and the traffic regulations, because I don
\rquote t.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What do we do there, Golan?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote To begin with, we\rquote re tourists, so that\rquote s the place where we\rquote d naturally go, and we want to be as inconspicuous and natural as we can. And secondly, where would you go to get information on Gaia?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote To a university\endash or an anthropological society\endash or a museum\endash Certainly not to a tourist center.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well, you\rquote re wrong. At the tourist center, we will be intellectual types who are eager to have a listing of the universities in the city and the museums and so on. We\rquote 
ll decide where to go to first and there we may find the proper people to consult concerning ancient history, galactography, mythology, anthropology, or anything else you can think of. \endash But the whole thing starts at the tourist center.\rdblquote 

\par \tab Pelorat was silent and the ground-car moved on in a tortuous manner as it joined and became part of the traffic pat
tern. They plunged into a sub-road and drove past signs that might have represented directions and traffic instructions but were in a style of lettering that made them all-but-unreadable.
\par \tab Fortunately the ground-car behaved as though it knew the way, and w
hen it stopped and drew itself into a parking spot, there was a sign that said: SAYSHELL OUT-WORLD MILIEU in the same difficult printing, and under it: SAYSHELL TOURIST CENTER in straightforward, easy-to-read Galactic Standard lettering.
\par \tab They walked into the building, which was not as large as the fa\'e7ade had led them to believe. It was certainly not busy inside.
\par \tab There were a series of waiting booths, one of which was occupied by a man reading the news-strips emerging from a small ejector; another containe
d two women who seemed to be playing some intricate game with cards and tiles. Behind a counter too large for him, with winking computer controls that seemed far too complex for him, was a bored-looking Sayshellian functionary wearing what looked like a m
ulticolored checkerboard.
\par \tab Pelorat stared and whispered, \ldblquote This is certainly a world of extroverted garb.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Trevize, \ldblquote I noticed. Still, fashions change from world to world and even from region to region within a world sometimes. And they change w
ith time. Fifty years ago, everyone on Sayshell might have worn black, for all we know. Take it as it comes, Janov.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I suppose I\rquote ll have to,\rdblquote  said Pelorat, \ldblquote but I prefer our own fashions. At least, they\rquote re not an assault upon the optic nerve.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Because so many of us are gray on gray? That offends some people. I\rquote ve heard it referred to as \lquote dressing in dirt.\rquote  Then too, it\rquote s Foundation colorlessness that probably keeps these people in their rainbows
\endash just to emphasize their independence. It\rquote s all what you\rquote re accustomed to, anyway.\endash Come on, Janov.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The two headed toward the counter and, as they did so, the man in the booth forsook his news items, rose, and came to meet them, smiling as he did so. His clothing was in shades of gray.
\par \tab Trevize didn\rquote t look in his direction at first, but when he did he stopped dead.
\par \tab He took a deep breath, \ldblquote By the Galaxy\endash My friend, the traitor!\rdblquote 
