\par \tab MUNN LI COMPOR, COUNCILMAN OF TERMINUS, LOOKED UNCERTAIN as he extended his right hand to Trevize.
\par \tab Trevize looked at the hand sternly and did not take it. He said, apparently to open air, \ldblquote 
I am in no position to create a situation in which I may find myself arrested for disturbing the peace on a foreign planet, but I will do so anyway if this individual comes a step closer.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor stopped abruptly, hesitated, and finally said in a low voice after glancing uncertainly at Pelorat, \ldblquote Am I to have a chance to talk? To explain? Will you listen?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat looked from one to the other with a slight frown on his long face. He said, \ldblquote What\rquote s all this, Golan? Have we come to this far world and at once met someone you know?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize\rquote s eyes remained firmly fixed on Compor, but he twisted his body slightly to make it clear that he was talking to Pelorat. Trevize said, \ldblquote This\endash human being\endash we would judge that much from his shape\endash 
was once a friend of mine on Terminus. As is my habit with my friends, I trusted him. I told him my views, which were perhaps not the kind that should have received a general airing. He told them to the autho
rities in great detail, apparently, and did not take the trouble to tell me he had done so. For that reason, I walked neatly into a trap and now I find myself in exile. And now this\endash human being\endash wishes to be recognized as a friend.\rdblquote 

\par \tab He turned to Compor full on and brushed his fingers through his hair, succeeding only in disarranging the curls further. \ldblquote 
See here, you. I do have a question for you. What are you doing here? Of all the worlds in the Galaxy on which you could be, why are you on this one? And why now?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor\rquote s hand, which had remained outstretched throughout Trevize\rquote 
s speech, now fell to his side and the smile left his face. The air of self-confidence, which was ordinarily so much a part of him, was gone and in its absence he looked younger than his thirty-four years and a bit woebegone. \ldblquote I\rquote 
ll explain,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote but only from the start!\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize looked about briefly. \ldblquote Here? You really want to talk about it here? In a public place? You want me to knock you down here after I\rquote ve listened to enough of your lies?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor lifted both hands now, palms facing each other. \ldblquote It\rquote s the safest place, believe me.\rdblquote  And then, checking himself and realizing what the other was about to say, added hurriedly, \ldblquote Or don\rquote 
t believe me, it doesn\rquote t matter. I\rquote m telling the truth. I\rquote ve been on the planet several hours longer than you and I\rquote ve checked it out. This is some particular day they have here on Sayshell. It\rquote 
s a day for meditation, for some reason. Almost everyone is at home\endash or should be.\endash You see how empty this place is. You don\rquote t suppose it\rquote s like this every day.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat nodded and said, \ldblquote I was wondering why it was so empty, at that.\rdblquote  He leaned toward Trevize\rquote s ear and whispered, \ldblquote Why not let him talk, Golan? He looks miserable, poor chap, and he may be trying to a
pologize. It seems unfair not to give him the chance to do so.\rquote ,
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote Dr. Pelorat seems anxious to hear you. I\rquote m willing to oblige him, but you\rquote ll oblige me if you\rquote 
re brief about it. This may be a good day on which to lose my temper. If everyone is meditating, any disturbance I cause may not produce the guardians of the law. I may not be so lucky tomorrow. Why waste an opportunity?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor said in a strained voice, \ldblquote Look, if you want to take a poke at me, do so. I won\rquote t even defend myself, see? Go ahead, hit me\endash but listen!\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Go ahead and talk, then. I\rquote ll listen for a while.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote In the first place, Golan\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Address me as Trevize, please. I am not on first-name terms with you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote In the first place, Trevize, you did too good a job convincing me of your views\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You hid that well. I could have sworn you were amused by me.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I tried to be amused to hide from myself the fact that you were being extremely disturbing.\endash Look, let us sit down up against the wall. Even if the place is empty, some few may come in and I don\rquote 
t think we ought to be needlessly conspicuous.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Slowly the three men walked most of the length of the large room. Compor was smiling tentatively again, but remained carefully at more than arm\rquote s length from Trevize.
\par \tab They sat each on a seat that gave as their weight was placed upon it and molded itself into the shape of their hips and buttocks. Pelorat looked surprised and made as though to stand up.
\par \tab \ldblquote Relax, Professor,\rdblquote  said Compor. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been through this already. They\rquote re in advance of us in some ways. It\rquote s a world that believes in small comforts.\rdblquote 
\par \tab He turned to Trevize, placing one arm over the back of his chair and speaking easily now. \ldblquote You disturbed me. You made me feel the Second Foundation did exist, and that was deeply upsetting. Consider the consequences if they did. Wasn
\rquote t it likely that they might take care of you somehow? Remove you as a menace? And if I behaved as though I believed you, I might be removed as well. Do you see my point?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I see a coward.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What good would it do to be storybook brave?\rdblquote  said Compor warmly, his blue eyes widening in indignation. \ldblquote Can you or I stand up to an organization capable of molding our minds and emotions? The onl
y way we could fight effectively would be to hide our knowledge to begin with.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote So you hid it and were safe?\endash Yet you didn\rquote t hide it from Mayor Branno, did you? Quite a risk there.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes! But I thought that was worth it. Just talking between ourselves might do nothing more than get ourselves mentally controlled\endash or our memories erased altogether. If I told the Mayor, on the other hand\endash 
 She knew my father well, you know. My father and I were immigrants from Smyrno and the Mayor had a grandmother who\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes yes,\rdblquote  said Trevize impatiently, \ldblquote and several generations farther back you can trace ancestry to the Sirius Sector. You\rquote ve told all that to everyone you know. Get on with it, Compor!\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well, I had her ear. If I could convince the Mayor that there was danger, using your arguments, the Federation might take some action. We\rquote re not as helpless as we were in the days of the Mule and\endash at the worst\endash 
this dangerous knowledge would be spread more widely and we ourselves would not be in as much specific danger.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said sardonically, \ldblquote Endanger the Foundation, but keep ourselves safe. That\rquote s good patriotic stuff.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote That would be at the worst. I was counting on the best.\rdblquote  His forehead had become a little damp. He seemed to be straining against Trevize\rquote s immovable contempt.
\par \tab \ldblquote And you didn\rquote t tell me of this clever plan of yours, did you?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No, I didn\rquote t and I\rquote m sorry about that, Trevize. The Mayor ordered me not to. She said she wanted to know everything you knew but that you were the sort of person who would freeze 
if you knew that your remarks were being passed on.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote How right she was!\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I didn\rquote t know\endash I couldn\rquote t guess\endash I had no way of conceiving that she was planning to arrest you and throw you off the planet.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote She was waiting for the right political moment, when my status as Councilman would not protect me. You didn\rquote t foresee that?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote How could I? You yourself did not.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Had I known that she knew my views, I would have.\rdblquote  
\par \tab Compor said with a sudden trace of insolence, \ldblquote That\rquote s easy enough to say\endash in hindsight.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And what is it you want of me here? Now that you have a bit of hindsight, too.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote To make up for all this. To make up for the harm I unwittingly\endash unwittingly\endash did you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Goodness,\rdblquote  said Trevize dryly. \ldblquote How kind of you! But you haven\rquote t answered my original question. How did you come to be here? How do you happen to be on the very planet I am on?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor said, \ldblquote There\rquote s no complicated answer necessary for that. I followed you!\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Through hyperspace? With my ship making Jumps in series?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor shook his head. \ldblquote No mystery. I have the same kind of a ship you do, with the same kind of computer. You know I\rquote ve always had this trick of being able to guess in which direction through hyperspace a ship would go. It\rquote 
s not usually a very good guess and I\rquote m wrong two times out of three, but with the computer I\rquote 
m much better. And you hesitated quite a bit at the start and gave me a chance to evaluate the direction and speed in which you were going before entering hyperspace. I fed the data\endash together with my own intuitive extrapolations\endash 
into the computer and it did the rest.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And you actually got to the city ahead of me?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes. You didn\rquote t use gravitics and I did. I guessed you would come to the capital city, so I went straight down, while you\endash \rdblquote  Compo
r made a short spiral motion with his finger as though it were a ship riding a directional beam.
\par \tab \ldblquote You took a chance on a run-in with Sayshellian officialdom.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well\endash \rdblquote  Compor\rquote s face broke into a smile that lent it an undeniable charm and Trevize felt himself almost warming to him. Compor said, \ldblquote I\rquote m not a coward at all times and in all things.\rdblquote 

\par \tab Trevize steeled himself. \ldblquote How did you happen to get a ship like mine?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote In precisely the same way you got a ship like yours. The old lady\endash Mayor Branno\endash assigned it to me.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I\rquote m being entirely frank with you. My assignment was to follow you. The Mayor wanted to know where you were going and what you would be doing.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And you\rquote ve been reporting faithfully to her, I suppose.\endash Or have you been faithless to the Mayor also?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I reported to her. I had no choice, actually. She placed a hyperrelay on board ship, which I wasn\rquote t supposed to find, but which I did find.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Unfortunately it\rquote s hooked up so that I can\rquote t remove it without immobilizing the vessel. At least, there\rquote s no way I can remove it. Consequently she knows where I am\endash and she knows where you are.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Suppose you hadn\rquote t been able to follow me. Then she wouldn\rquote t have known where I was. Had you thought of that?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of course I did. I thought of just reporting I had lost you\endash but she wouldn\rquote t have believed me, would she? And I wouldn\rquote t have been able to get back to Terminus for who knows how long. And I\rquote 
m not like you, Trevize. I\rquote m not a carefree person without attachments. I have a wife on Terminus\endash a pregnant wife\endash and I want to get back to her. You can afford to think only of yourself. I can\rquote t.\endash Besides, I\rquote 
ve come to warn you. By Seldon, I\rquote m trying to do that and you won\rquote t listen. You keep talking about other things.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I\rquote m not impressed by your sudden conc
ern for me. What can you warn me against? It seems to me that you are the only thing I need be warned about. You betray me, and now you follow me in order to betray me again. No one else is doing me any harm.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor said earnestly, \ldblquote Forget the dramatics, man. Trevize, you\rquote re a lightning rod! You\rquote ve been sent out to draw Second Foundation response\endash 
if there is such a thing as the Second Foundation. I have an intuitive sense for things other than hyperspatial pursuit and I\rquote m sure that\rquote s what she\rquote s planning. If you try to find the Second Foundation, they\rquote 
ll become aware of it and they\rquote ll act against you. If they do, they are very likely to tip their hand. And when they do, Mayor Branno will go for them.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote A pity your famous intuition wasn\rquote t working when Branno was planning my arrest.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor flushed and muttered, \ldblquote You know it doesn\rquote t always work.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And now it tells you she\rquote s planning to attack the Second Foundation. She wouldn\rquote t dare.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I think she would. But that\rquote s not the point. The point is that right now she is throwing you out as bait.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote So?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote So by all the black holes in space, don\rquote t search for the Second Foundation. She won\rquote t care if you\rquote re killed in the search, but I care. I feel responsible for this and I care.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I\rquote m touched,\rdblquote  said Trevize coldly, \ldblquote but as it happens I have another task on hand at the moment.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You have?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Pelorat and I are on the track of Earth, the planet that some think was the original home of the human race. Aren\rquote t we, Janov?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat nodded his head. \ldblquote Yes, it\rquote s a purely scientific matter and a long-standing interest of mine.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor looked blank for a moment. Then, \ldblquote Looking for Earth? But why?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote To study it,\rdblquote  said Pelorat. \ldblquote As the one world on which human beings developed\endash presumably from lower forms of life, instead of, as on all others, merely arriving ready-made\endash 
it should be a fascinating study in uniqueness.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And,\rdblquote  said Trevize, \ldblquote as a world where, just possibly, I may learn more of the Second Foundation.\endash Just possibly.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor said, \ldblquote But there isn\rquote t any Earth. Didn\rquote t you know that?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No Earth?\rdblquote  Pelorat looked utterly blank, as he always did when he was preparing to be stubborn. \ldblquote Are you saying there was no planet on which the human species originated?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Oh no. Of course, there was an Earth. There\rquote s no question of that! But there isn\rquote t any Earth now. No inhabited Earth. It\rquote s gone!\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, unmoved, \ldblquote There are tales\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Hold on, Janov,\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote Tell me, Compor, how do you know this?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What do you mean, how? It\rquote s my heritage. I trace my ancestry from the Sirius Sector, if I may repeat that fact without boring you. We know all about Earth out there. It exists in that sector, which means it\rquote 
s not part of the Foundation Federation, so apparently no one on Terminus bothers with it. But that\rquote s where Earth is, just the same.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote That is one suggestion, yes,\rdblquote  said Pelorat. \ldblquote There was considerable enthusiasm for that \lquote Sirius Alternative,\rquote  as they called it, in the days of the Empire.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Compor said vehemently. \ldblquote It\rquote s not an alternative. It\rquote s a fact.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote What would you say if I told you I know of many different places in the Galaxy that are called Earth\endash or were called Earth\endash by the people who lived in its stellar neighborhood?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote But this is the real thing,\rdblquote  said Compor. \ldblquote The Sirius Sector is the longest-inhabited portion of the Galaxy. Everyone knows that.\rdblquote 
