\par \tab Sura Novi had her palm to her furrowed brow. \ldblquote Your pardon, Master, I be struck with sudden head-anguish.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Gendibal was instantly contrite. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, Novi. I wasn\rquote t thinking\endash or I was thinking too intently.\rdblquote  Instantly\endash and gently\endash he smoothed the ruffled mind tendrils.
\par \tab Novi smiled with sudden brightness. \ldblquote It passed with sudden vanishing. The kind sound of your words, Master, works well upon me.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Gendibal said, \ldblquote Good! Is something wrong? Why are you here?\rdblquote  He forbore to enter her mind in greater detail in order to find out for himself. More and more, he felt a reluctance to invade her privacy.
\par \tab Novi hesitated. She leaned toward him slightly. \ldblquote I be concerned. You were looking at nothing and making sounds and your face was twitching. I stayed there, stick-frozen, afeared you were declining\endash  ill\endash 
and unknowing what to do.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It was nothing, Novi. You are not to fear.\rdblquote  He patted her nearer hand. \ldblquote There is nothing to fear. Do you understand?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Fear\endash or any strong emotion\endash twisted and spoiled the symmetry of her mind somewhat. He preferred it calm and peaceful and happy, but he hesitated at the thought of adjusting it into tha
t position by outer influence. She had felt the previous adjustment to be the effect of his words and it seemed to him that he preferred it that way.
\par \tab He said, \ldblquote Novi, why don\rquote t I call you Sura?\rdblquote 
\par \tab She looked up at him in sudden woe. \ldblquote Oh, Master, do not do so.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote But Rufirant did so on that day that we met. I know you well enough now\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I know well he did so, Master. It be how a man speak to girl who have no man, no betrothed, who is\endash not complete. You say her previous. It is more honorable for me if you say \lquote Novi\rquote 
 and I be proud that you say so. And if I have not man now, I have master and I be pleased. I hope it be not offensive to you to say \lquote Novi.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It certainly isn\rquote t, Novi.\rdblquote 
\par \tab And her mind was beautifully smooth at that and Gendibal was pleased. Too pleased. Ought he to be so pleased?
\par \tab A little shamefacedly, he remembered that the Mule was supposed to have been affected in this manner by that woman of the First Foundation, Bayta Darell, to his own undoing.
\par \tab This, of course, was different. This Hamishwoman was his defense against alien minds and he wanted her to serve that purpose most efficiently.
\par \tab No, that was not true\endash His function as a Speaker would be compromised if he ceased to understand his own mind or, worse, if he deliberately misconstrued it to avo
id the truth. The truth was that it pleased him when she was calm and peaceful and happy endogenously\endash without his interference\endash 
and that it pleased him simply because she pleased him; and (he thought defiantly) there was nothing wrong with that.
\par \tab He said, \ldblquote Sit down, Novi.\rdblquote 
\par \tab She did so, balancing herself precariously at the edge of the chair and sitting as far away as the confines of the room allowed. Her mind was flooded with respect.
\par \tab He said, \ldblquote When you saw me making sounds, Novi, I was speaking at a long distance, scholar-fashion.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Novi said sadly, her eyes cast down, \ldblquote I see, Master, that there be much to scowler-fashion I understand not and imagine not. It be difficult mountain-high art. I be 
