\par \tab \ldblquote No, of course not, but I may have read papers of his. Back at the ship, where I have my reference collection\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote We\rquote re not going back, Janov. If the name is familiar, that\rquote s a starting point. If he can\rquote t help us, he will undoubtedly be able to direct us further.\rdblquote  He rose to his feet. \ldblquote Let\rquote 
s find a way of getting to Sayshell University. And since there will be nobody there at lunchtime, let\rquote s eat first.\rdblquote 
\par \tab It was not till late afternoon that they had made their way out to the university, worked their way through its maze, and found themselves in an anteroom, waiting for a young woman who had gone off in search of information and who might\endash 
or might not\endash lead them to Quintesetz.
\par \tab \ldblquote I wonder,\rdblquote  said Pelorat uneasily, \ldblquote how much longer we\rquote ll have to wait. It must be getting toward the close of the schoolday.\rdblquote 
\par \tab And, as though that were a cue, the young lady whom they had last seen half an hour before, walked rapidly toward them, her shoes glinting red and violet and striking the ground with a sharp musical tone as she w
alked. The pitch varied with the speed and force of her steps.
\par \tab Pelorat winced. He supposed that each world had its own ways of assaulting the senses, just as each had its own smell. He wondered if, now that he no longer noticed the smell, he might also le
arn not to notice the cacophony of fashionable young women when they walked.
\par \tab She came to Pelorat and stopped. \ldblquote May I have your full name, Professor?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It\rquote s Janov Pelorat, miss.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Your home planet?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize began to lift one hand as though to enjoin silence, but Pelorat, either not seeing or not regarding, said, \ldblquote Terminus.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The young woman smiled broadly, and looked pleased. \ldblquote When I told Professor Quintesetz that a Professor Pelorat was inquiring for him, he said he would see you if you were Janov Pelorat of Terminus, but not otherwise.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat blinked rapidly. \ldblquote You\endash you mean, he\rquote s heard of me?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It certainly seems so.\rdblquote 
\par \tab And, almost creakily, Pelorat managed a smile as he turned to Trevize. \ldblquote He\rquote s heard of me. I honestly didn\rquote t think\endash I mean, I\rquote ve written very few papers and I didn\rquote t think that anyone\endash \rdblquote 
 He shook his head. \ldblquote They weren\rquote t really important.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well then,\rdblquote  said Trevize, smiling himself, \ldblquote stop hugging yourself in an ecstasy of self-underestimation and let\rquote s go.\rdblquote  He turned to the woman. \ldblquote I presume, miss, there\rquote 
s some sort of transportation to take us to him?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It\rquote s within walking distance. We won\rquote t even have to leave the building complex and I\rquote ll be glad to take you there.\endash Are both of you from Terminus?\rdblquote  And off she went.
\par \tab The two men followed and Trevize said, with a trace of annoyance, \ldblquote Yes, we are. Does that make a difference?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Oh no, of course not. There are people on Sayshell that don\rquote t like Foundationers, you know, but here at the university, we\rquote re more cosmopolitan than that. Live and le
t live is what I always say. I mean, Foundationers are people, too. You know what I mean?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes, I know what you mean. Lots of us say that Sayshellians are people.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote That\rquote s just the way it should be. I\rquote ve never seen Terminus. It must be a big city.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Actually it isn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Trevize matter-of-factly. \ldblquote I suspect it\rquote s smaller than Sayshell City.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You\rquote re tweaking my finger,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote It\rquote s the capital of the Foundation Federation, isn\rquote t it? I mean, there isn\rquote t another Terminus, is there?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No, there\rquote s only one Terminus, as far as I know, and that\rquote s where we\rquote re from\endash the capital of the Foundation Federation.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well then, it must be an enormous city. \endash And you\rquote re coming all the way here to see the professor. We\rquote re very proud of him, you know. He\rquote s considered the biggest authority in the whole Galaxy.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Really?\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote On what?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Her eyes opened wide again, \ldblquote You are a teaser. He knows more about ancient history than\endash than I know about my own family.\rdblquote  And she continued to walk on ahead on her musical feet.
\par \tab One can only be called a teaser and a finger-tweaker so often without developing an actual impulse in that direction. Trevize smiled and said, \ldblquote The professor knows all about Earth, I suppose?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Earth?\rdblquote  She stopped at an office door and looked at them blankly.
\par \tab \ldblquote You know. The world where humanity got its start.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Oh, you mean the planet-that-was-first. I guess so. I guess he should know all about it. After all, it\rquote s located in the Sayshell Sector. Everyone knows that!\endash This is his office. Let me signal him.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No, don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote Not for just a minute. Tell me about Earth.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Actually I never heard anyone call it Earth. I suppose that\rquote s a Foundation word. We call it Gaia, here.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize cast a swift look at Pelorat. \ldblquote Oh? And where is it located?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Nowhere. It\rquote s in hyperspace and there\rquote s no way anyone can get to it. When I was a little girl, my grandmother said that Gaia was once in real space, but it was so disgusted at the\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Crimes and stupidities of human beings,\rdblquote  muttered Pelorat, \ldblquote that, out of shame, it left space and refused to have anything more to do with the human beings it had sent out into the Galaxy.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You know the story, then. See?\endash A girlfriend of mine says it\rquote s superstition. Well, I\rquote ll tell her. If it\rquote s good enough for professors from the Foundation\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab A glittering section of lettering on the smoky glass of the door read: SOTAYN QUINTESETZ ABT in the hard-to-read Sayshellian calligraphy\endash and under it was printed, in the same fashion: DEPARTMENT OF ANCIENT HISTORY.
\par \tab The woman placed her finger on a smooth metal circle. There was no sound, but the smokiness of the glass turned a milky white for a moment and a soft voice said, in an abstracted sort of way, \ldblquote Identify yourself, please.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Janov Pelorat of Terminus,\rdblquote  said Pelorat, \ldblquote with Golan Trevize of the same world.\rdblquote  The door swung open at once.
\par \tab The man who stood up, walked around his desk, and advanced to meet them was tall and well into middle age. He was light brown in skin color and h
is hair, which was set in crisp curls over his head, was iron-gray. He held out his hand in greeting and his voice was soft and low. \ldblquote I am S.Q. I am delighted to meet you, Professors.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote I don\rquote t own an academic title. I merely accompany Professor Pelorat. You may call me simply Trevize. I am pleased to meet you, Professor Abt.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz held up one hand in clear embarrassment. \ldblquote No no. Abt is merely a foolish title of some sort that has no significance outside of Sayshell. Ignore it, please,
 and call me S.Q. We tend to use initials in ordinary social intercourse on Sayshell. I\rquote m so pleased to meet two of you when I had been expecting but one.\rdblquote 
\par \tab He seemed to hesitate a moment, then extended his right hand after wiping it unobtrusively on his trousers.
\par \tab Trevize took it, wondering what the proper Sayshellian manner of greeting was.
\par \tab Quintesetz said, \ldblquote Please sit down. I\rquote m afraid you\rquote ll find these chairs to be lifeless ones, but I, for one, don\rquote t want my chairs to hug me. It\rquote s all the fashion for c
hairs to hug you nowadays, but I prefer a hug to mean something, hey?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize smiled and said, \ldblquote Who would not? Your name, S.Q., seems to be of the Rim Worlds and not Sayshellian. I apologize if the remark is impertinent.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I don\rquote t mind. My family traces back, in part, to Askone. Five generations back, my great-great-grandparents left Askone when Foundation domination grew too heavy.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote And we are Foundationers. Our apologies.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz waved his hand genially, \ldblquote I don\rquote t hold a grudge across a stretch of five generations. Not that such things haven\rquote t been done, more\rquote 
s the pity. Would you like to have something to eat? To drink? Would you like music in the background?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote If you don\rquote t mind,\rdblquote  said Pelorat, \ldblquote I\rquote d be willing to get right to business, if Sayshellian ways would permit.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Sayshellian ways are not a barrier to that, I assure you.\endash You have no idea how remarkable this is, Dr. Pelorat. It was only about two weeks ago that I came across your article on origin myths in the Archaeological 
Review and it struck me as a remarkable synthesis\endash all too brief.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat flushed with pleasure. \ldblquote How delighted I am that you have read it. I had to condense it, of course, since the Review would not print a full study. I have been planning to do a treatise on the subject.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I wish you would. In any case, as soon as I had read it, I had this desire to see you. I even had the notion of visiting Terminus in order to do so, though that would have been hard to arrange\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why so?\rdblquote  asked Trevize.
\par \tab Quintesetz looked embarrassed. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry to say that Sayshell is not eager to join the Foundation Federation and rather discourages any social communication with the Foundation. We\rquote 
ve a tradition of neutralism, you see. Even the Mule didn\rquote t bother us, except to extort from us a specific statement of neutrality. For that reason, any application for permission to visit Foundation territory generally\endash 
and particularly Terminus\endash is viewed with suspicion, although a scholar such as myself, intent on academic business, would probably obtain his passport in the end.\endash 
But none of that was necessary; you have come to me. I can scarcely believe it. I ask myself: Why? Have you heard of me, as I have heard of you?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote 
I know your work, S.Q., and in my records I have abstracts of your papers. It is why I have come to you. I am exploring both the matter of Earth, which is the reputed planet of origin of the human species, and the early period of the exploration and settl
ement of the Galaxy. In particular, I have come here to inquire as to the founding of Sayshell.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote From your paper,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote I presume you are interested in myths and legends.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Even more in history\endash actual facts\endash if such exist. Myths and legends, otherwise.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz rose and walked rapidly back and forth the length of his office, paused to stare at Pelorat, then walked again.
\par \tab Trevize said impatiently, \ldblquote Well, sir.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz said, \ldblquote Odd! Really odd! It was only yesterday\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote What was only yesterday?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz said, \ldblquote I told you, Dr. Pelorat\endash may I call you J.P., by the way? I find using a full-length name rather unnatural.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Please do.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I told you, J.P., that I had admired your paper and that I had wanted to see you. The reason I wanted to see you was that you clearly had an extensive collection of legends concerning the beginnings of the worlds and yet didn\rquote 
t have ours. In other words, I wanted to see you in order to tell you precisely what you have come to see me to find out.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What has this to do with yesterday, S.Q.?\rdblquote  asked Trevize.
\par \tab \ldblquote We have legends. A legend. An important one to our society, for it has become our central mystery\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Mystery?\rdblquote  said Trevize.
\par \tab \ldblquote I don\rquote t mean a puzzle or anything of that sort. That, I believe, would be the usual meaning of the word in Galactic Standard. There\rquote s a specialized meaning here. It means \lquote something secret\rquote 
; something only certain adepts know the full meaning of; something not to be spoken of to outsiders.\endash And yesterday was the day.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The day of what, S.Q.?\rdblquote  asked Trevize, slightly exaggerating his air of patience.
\par \tab \ldblquote Yesterday was the Day of Flight.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Trevize, \ldblquote a day of meditation and quiet, when everyone is supposed to remain at home.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Something like that, in theory, except that in the larger cities, the more sophisticated regions, there is little observance in the older fashion.\endash But you know about it, I see.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat, who had grown uneasy at Trevize\rquote s annoyed tone, put in hastily, \ldblquote We heard a little of it, having arrived yesterday.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of all days,\rdblquote  said Trevize sarcastically. \ldblquote See here, S.Q. As I said, I\rquote 
m not an academic, but I have a question. You said you were speaking of a central mystery, meaning it was not to be spoken of to outsiders. Why, then, are you speaking of it to us? We are outsiders.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote So you are. But I\rquote m not an observer of the day and the depth of my superstition in this matter is slight at best. J.P.\rquote s paper, however, reinforced a feeling I have had for a long time. A myth or legend is simply not made up
 out of a vacuum. Nothing is\endash or can be. Somehow there is a kernel of truth behind it, however distorted that might be, and I would like the truth behind our legend of the Day of Flight.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote Is it safe to talk about it?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz shrugged. \ldblquote Not entirely, I suppose. The conservative elements among our population would be horrified. However, they don\rquote t control the government and haven\rquote 
t for a century. The secularists are strong and would be stronger still, if the conservatives didn\rquote t take advantage of our\endash if you\rquote ll excuse me\endash 
anti-Foundation bias. Then, too, since I am discussing the matter out of my scholarly interest in ancient history, the League of Academicians will support me strongly, in case of need.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote In that case,\rdblquote  said Pelorat, \ldblquote would you tell us about your central mystery, SQ.?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes, but let me make sure we won\rquote t be interrupted or, for that matter, overheard. Even if one must stare the bull in the face, one needn\rquote t slap its muzzle, as the saying goes.\rdblquote 
\par \tab He flicked a pattern on the work-face of an instrument on his desk and said, \ldblquote We\rquote re incommunicado now.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Are you sure you\rquote re not bugged?\rdblquote  asked Trevize.
\par \tab \ldblquote Bugged?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Tapped! Eavesdropped! \endash Subjected to a device that will have you under observation\endash visual or auditory or both.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz looked shocked. \ldblquote Not here on Sayshell!\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize shrugged. \ldblquote If you say so.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Please go on, SQ.,\rdblquote  said Pelorat.
\par \tab Quintesetz pursed his lips, leaned back in his chair (which gave slightly under the pressure) and put the tips of his fingers together. He seemed to be speculating as to just how to begin.
\par \tab He said, \ldblquote Do you know what a robot is?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote A robot?\rdblquote  said Pelorat. \ldblquote No.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz looked in the direction of Trevize, who shook his head slowly.
\par \tab \ldblquote You know what a computer is, however?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of course,\rdblquote  said Trevize impatiently.
\par \tab \ldblquote Well then, a mobile computerized tool\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Is a mobile computerized tool.\rdblquote  Trevize was still impatient. \ldblquote There are endless varieties and I don\rquote t know of any generalized term for it except mobile computerized tool.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote \endash that looks exactly like a human being is a robot.\rdblquote  S.Q. completed his definition with equanimity. \ldblquote The distinction of a robot is that it is humaniform.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why humaniform?\rdblquote  asked Pelorat in honest amazement. 
\par \tab \ldblquote I\rquote m not sure. It\rquote s a remarkably inefficient form for a tool, I grant you, but I\rquote m just repeating the legend. \lquote Robot\rquote 
 is an old word from no recognizable language, though our scholars say it bears the connotation of \lquote work.' \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I can\rquote t think of any word,\rdblquote  said Trevize skeptically, \ldblquote that sounds even vaguely like \lquote robot\rquote  and that has any connection with \lquote work.' \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Nothing in Galactic, certainly,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote but that\rquote s what they say.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote It may have been reverse etymology. These objects were used for work, and so the word was said to mean \lquote work.\rquote  \endash In any case, why do you tell us this?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Because it is a firmly fixed tradition here on Sayshell that when Earth was a single world and the Galaxy lay all uninhabited before it, robots were invented and devised. There were then two sorts of human bei
ngs: natural and invented, flesh and metal, biological and mechanical, complex and simple\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz came to a halt and said with a rueful laugh, \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry. It is impossible to talk about robots without quoting from the Book of Flight. The people of Earth devised robots\endash and I need say no more. That\rquote 
s plain enough.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And why did they devise robots?\rdblquote  asked Trevize.
\par \tab Quintesetz shrugged. \ldblquote Who can tell at this distance in time? Perhaps they were few in numbers and needed help, particularly in the great task of exploring and populating the Galaxy.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote That\rquote s a reasonable suggestion. Once the Galaxy was colonized, the robots would no longer be needed. Certainly there are no humanoid mobile computerized tools in the Galaxy today.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote In any case,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote the story is as follows\endash if I may vastly simplify and leave out many poetic ornamentations which, frankly, I don\rquote 
t accept, though the general population does or pretends to. Around Earth, there grew up colony worlds circling neighboring st
ars and these colony worlds were far richer in robots than was Earth itself. There was more use for robots on raw, new worlds. Earth, in fact, retreated, wished no more robots, and rebelled against them.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote  asked Pelorat.
\par \tab \ldblquote The Outer Worlds were the stronger. With the help of their robots, the children defeated and controlled Earth\endash the Mother. Pardon me, but I can\rquote 
t help slipping into quotation. But there were those from Earth who fled their world\endash with better ships and stronger modes of hype
rspatial travel. They fled to far distant stars and worlds, far beyond the closer worlds earlier colonized. New colonies were founded\endash without robots\endash 
in which human beings could live freely. Those were the Times of Flight, so-called, and the day upon which the first Earthmen reached the Sayshell Sector\endash  this very planet, in fact\endash 
is the Day of Flight, celebrated annually for many thousands of years.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote My dear chap, what you are saying, then, is that Sayshell was founded directly from Earth.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz thought and hesitated for a moment. Then he said, \ldblquote That is the official belief.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Obviously,\rdblquote  said Trevize, \ldblquote you don\rquote t accept it.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It seems to me\endash \rdblquote  Quintesetz began and then burst out, \ldblquote Oh, Great Stars and Small Planets, I don\rquote t! It is entirely too unlikely, but it\rquote 
s official dogma and however secularized the government has become, lip service to that, at least, is essential.\endash Still, to the point. In your article, J.P., there is no indication that you\rquote re aware of this story\endash of robots and of two 
waves of colonization, a lesser one with robots and a greater one without.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I certainly was not,\rdblquote  said Pelorat. \ldblquote 
I hear it now for the first time and, my dear SQ., I am eternally grateful to you for making this known to me. I am astonished that no hint of this has appeared in any of the writings\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It shows,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote how effective our social system is. It\rquote s our Sayshellian secret\endash our great mystery.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Perhaps,\rdblquote  said Trevize dryly. \ldblquote Yet the second wave of colonization\endash the robotless wave\endash must have moved out in all directions. Why is it only on Sayshell that this great secret exists?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz said, \ldblquote It may exist elsewhere and be just as secret. Our own conservatives believe that only Sayshell was settled from Earth and that all the rest of the Galaxy was settled from Sayshell. That, of course, is probably nonsense.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote These subsidiary puzzles 
can be worked out in time. Now that I have the starting point, I can seek out similar information on other worlds. What counts is that I have discovered the question to ask and a good question is, of course, the key by which infinite answers can be educed
. How fortunate that I\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote Yes, Janov, but the good S.Q. has not told us the whole story, surely. What happened to the older colonies and their robots? Do your traditions say?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Not in detail, but in essence. Human and humanoid cannot live together, apparently. The worlds with robots died. They were not viable.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And Earth?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Humans left it and settled here and presumably (though the conservatives would disagree) on other planets as well.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Surely not every human being left Earth. The planet was not deserted.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Presumably not. I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said abruptly, \ldblquote Was it left radioactive?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz looked astonished. \ldblquote Radioactive?\rdblquote  \ldblquote That\rquote s what I\rquote m asking.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Not to my knowledge. I never heard of such a thing.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize put a knuckle to his teeth and considered. Finally he said, \ldblquote S.Q., it\rquote s getting late and we have trespassed sufficiently on your time, perhaps.\rdblquote  (Pelorat made a motion as though he were about to protest, but Trevize
\rquote s hand was on the other\rquote s knee and his grip tightened\endash so Pelorat, looking disturbed, subsided.)
\par \tab Quintesetz said, \ldblquote I was delighted to be of use.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You have been and if there\rquote s anything we can do in exchange, name it.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz laughed gently. \ldblquote If the good J.P. will be so kind as to refrain from mentioning my name in connection with any writing he does on our mystery, that will be sufficient repayment.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said eagerly, \ldblquote You would be able to get the credit you deserve\endash and perhaps be more appreciated\endash if you were allowed to visit Terminus and even, perha
ps, remain there as a visiting scholar at our university for an extended period. We might arrange that. Sayshell might not like the Federation, but they might not like refusing a direct request that you be allowed to come to Terminus to attend, let us say
, a colloquium on some aspect of ancient history.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The Sayshellian half-rose. \ldblquote Are you saying you can pull strings to arrange that?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote Why, I hadn\rquote t thought of it, but J.P. is perfectly right. That would be feasible\endash if we tried. And, of course, the more grateful you make us, the harder we will try.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz paused, then frowned. \ldblquote What do you mean, sir?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote All you have to do is tell us about Gaia, S.Q.,\rdblquote  said Trevize. And all the light in Quintesetz\rquote s face died.
\par \tab Quintesetz looked down at his desk. His hand stroked absent-mindedly at his short, tightly curled hair. Then he looked at Trevize and pursed his lips tightly. It was as though he were determined not to speak.
\par \tab Trevize lifted his eyebrows and waited and finally Quintesetz said in a strangled sort of way, \ldblquote it is getting indeed late\endash quite glemmering.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Until then he had spoken in good Galactic, but now his words took on a strange shape as though the Sayshellian mode of speech were pushing past his classical education.
\par \tab \ldblquote Glemmering, S.Q.?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It is nearly full night.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize nodded. \ldblquote I am thoughtless. And I am hungry, too. Could you please join us for an evening meal, S.Q., at our expense? We could then, perhaps, continue our discussion\endash about Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz rose heavily to his feet. He was taller than either of the two men from Terminus, but he was older and pudgier and his height did not lend him the appearance of strength. He seemed more weary than when they had arrived.
\par \tab He blinked at them and said, \ldblquote 
I forget my hospitality. You are Outworlders and it would not be fitting that you entertain me. Come to my home. It is on campus and not far and, if you wish to carry on a conversation, I can do so in a more relaxed manner there than here. My only regret
\rdblquote  (he seemed a little uneasy) \ldblquote is that I can offer you only a limited meal. My wife and I are vegetarians and if you are meat-eating, I can only express my apologies and regrets.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote J.P. and I will be quite content to forego our carnivorous natures for one meal. Your conversation will more than make up for it\endash I hope.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I can promise you an interesting meal, whatever the conversation,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote if your taste should run to our Sayshellian spices. My wife and I have made a rare study of such things.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I look forward to any exoticism you choose to supply, S.Q.,\rdblquote  said Trevize coolly, though Pelorat looked a little nervous at the prospect.
\par \tab Quintesetz led the way. The three left the room and walked down an apparently endless corridor, 
with the Sayshellian greeting students and colleagues now and then, but making no attempt to introduce his companions. Trevize was uneasily aware that others stared curiously at his sash, which happened to be one of his gray ones. A subdued color was not 
something that was de rigueur in campus clothing, apparently.
\par \tab Finally they stepped through the door and out into the open. It was indeed dark and a little cool, with trees bulking in the distance and a rather rank stand of grass on either side of the walkway.
\par \tab Pelorat came to a halt\endash with his back to the glimmer of lights that came from the building they had just left and from the glows that lined the walks of the campus. He looked straight upward.
\par \tab \ldblquote Beautiful!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote There is a famous phrase in a verse by one of our better poets that speaks of \lquote the speckle-shine of Sayshell\rquote s soaring sky.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize gazed appreciately and said in a low voice, \ldblquote We are from Terminus, S.Q., and my friend, at least, has seen no other skies. On Terminus, we see only the smooth
 dim fog of the Galaxy and a few barely visible stars. You would appreciate your own sky even more, had you lived with ours.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz said gravely, \ldblquote We appreciate it to the full, I assure you. It\rquote s not so much that we are in an uncrowded area of the Galaxy, but that the distribution of stars is remarkably even. I don\rquote 
t think that you will find, anywhere in the Galaxy, first-magnitude stars so generally distributed. \endash And yet not too many, either. I have seen the skies of worlds that are inside the outer 
reaches of a globular cluster and there you will see too many bright stars. It spoils the darkness of the night sky and reduces the splendor considerably.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I quite agree with that,\rdblquote  said Trevize.
\par \tab \ldblquote Now I wonder,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote if you see that almost regular pentagon of almost equally bright stars. The Five Sisters, we call them. It\rquote s in that direction, just above the line of trees. Do you see it?
\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I see it,\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote Very attractive.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz. \ldblquote It\rquote s supposed to symbolize success in love \endash and there\rquote s no love letter that doesn\rquote 
t end in a pentagon of dots to indicate a desire to make love. Each of the five stars stands for a different stage in the process and there are famous poems which have vied with each other in making each sta
ge as explicitly erotic as possible. In my younger days, I attempted versifying on the subject myself and I wouldn\rquote t have thought that the time would come when I would grow so indifferent to the Five Sisters, though I suppose it\rquote 
s the common fate.\endash Do you see the dim star just about in the center of the Five Sisters.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote That,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote is supposed to represent unrequited love. There is a legend that the star was once as bright as the rest, but faded with grief.\rdblquote  And he walked on rapidly.
\par \tab The dinner, Trevize had been forced to admit to himself, was delightful. There was endless variety and the spicing and dressing were subtle but effective.
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote All these vegetables\endash which have been a pleasure to eat, by the way\endash are part of the Galactic dietary, are they not, SQ.?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes, of course.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I presume, though, that there are indigenous forms of life, too.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of course. Sayshell Planet was an oxygen world when the first settlers arrived, so it had to be life-bearing. And we have preserved some of t
he indigenous life, you may be sure. We have quite extensive natural parks in which both the flora and the fauna of Old Sayshell survive.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said sadly, \ldblquote There you are in advance of us, S.Q. There was little land life on Terminus when human beings arrived and I\rquote 
m afraid that for a long time no concerted effort was made to preserve the sea life, which had produced the oxygen that made Terminus habitable. Terminus has an ecology now that is purely Galactic in nature.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Sayshell,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, with a smile of modest pride, \ldblquote has a long and steady record of life-valuing.\rdblquote 
\par \tab And Trevize chose that moment to say, \ldblquote When we left your office, S.Q., I believe it was your intention to feed us dinner and then tell us about Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz\rquote s wife, a friendly woman\endash plump and quite dark, who had said little during the meal\endash looked up in astonishment, rose, and left the room without a word.
\par \tab \ldblquote My wife,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz uneasily, \ldblquote is quite a conservative, I\rquote m afraid, and is a bit uneasy at the mention of\endash the world. Please excuse her. But why do you ask about it?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Because it is important for J.P.\rquote s work, I\rquote m afraid.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote But why do you ask it of me? We were discussing Earth, robots, the founding of Sayshell. What has all this to do with\endash what you ask?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \lquote Perhaps nothi
ng, and yet there are so many oddnesses about the matter. Why is your wife uneasy at the mention of Gaia? Why are you uneasy? Some talk of it easily enough. We have been told only today that Gaia is Earth itself and that it has disappeared into hyperspace
 because of the evil done by human beings.\rdblquote 
\par \tab A look of pain crossed Quintesetz\rquote s face. \ldblquote Who told you that gibberish?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Someone I met here at the university.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote That\rquote s just superstition.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Then it\rquote s not part of the central dogma of your legends concerning the Flight?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No, of course not. It\rquote s just a fable that arose among the ordinary, uneducated people.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Are you sure?\rdblquote  asked Trevize coldly.
\par \tab Quintesetz sat back in his chair and stared at the remnant of the meal before him. \ldblquote Come into the living room,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote My wife will not allow this room to be cleared and set to rights while we are here and discussing
\endash this.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Are you sure it is just a fable?\rdblquote  repeated Trevize, once they had seated themselves in another room, before a window that bellied upward and inward to give a clear view of Sayshell\rquote 
s remarkable night sky. The lights within the room glimmered down to avoid competition and Quintesetz\rquote s dark countenance melted into the shadow.
\par \tab Quintesetz said, \ldblquote Aren\rquote t you sure? Do you think that any world can dissolve into hyperspace? You must understand that the average person has only the vaguest notion of what hyperspace is.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The truth is,\rdblquote  said Trevize, \ldblquote that I myself have only the vaguest notion of what hyperspace is and I\rquote ve been through it hundreds of times.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Let me speak realities, then. I assure you that Earth\endash wherever it is\endash is not located within the borders of the Sayshell Union and that the world you mentioned is not Earth.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote But even if you don\rquote t know where Earth is, S.Q., you ought to know where the world I mentioned is. It is certainly within the borders of the Sayshell Union. We know that much, eh, Pelorat?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat, who had been listening stolidly, started at being suddenly addressed and said, \ldblquote If it comes to that, Golan, I know where it is.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize turned to look at him. \ldblquote Since when, Janov?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Since earlier this evening, my dear Golan. You showed us the Five Sisters, S.Q., on our way from your office to your house. You pointed out a dim star at the center of the pentagon. I\rquote m positive that\rquote s Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz hesitated\endash his face, hidden in the dimness, was beyond any chance of interpretation. Finally he said, \ldblquote Well, that\rquote s what our astronomers tell us\endash privately. It is a planet that circles that star.\rdblquote 

\par \tab Trevize gazed contemplatively at Pelorat, but the expression on the professor\rquote s face was unreadable. Trevize turned to Quintesetz, \ldblquote Then tell us about that star. Do you have its co-ordinates?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I? No.\rdblquote  He was almost violent in his denial. \ldblquote I have no stellar co-ordinates here. You can get it from our astronomy department, though I imagine not without trouble. No travel to that star is permitted.\rdblquote 

\par \tab \ldblquote Why not? It\rquote s within your territory, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Spaciographically, yes. Politically, no.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize waited for something more to be said. When that didn\rquote t come, he rose. \ldblquote Professor Quintesetz,\rdblquote  he said formally, \ldblquote 
I am not a policeman, soldier, diplomat, or thug. I am not here to force information out of you. Instead, I shall, against my will, g
o to our ambassador. Surely, you must understand that it is not I, for my own personal interest, that request this information. This is Foundation business and I don\rquote t want to make an interstellar incident out of this. I don\rquote 
t think the Sayshell Union would want to, either.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz said uncertainly, \ldblquote What is this Foundation business?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote That\rquote s not something I can discuss with you. If Gaia is not something you can discuss with me, then we will transfer it all to the government level and, under the circu
mstances, it may be the worse for Sayshell. Sayshell has kept its independence of the Federation and I have no objection to that. I have no reason to wish Sayshell ill and I do not wish to approach our ambassador. In fact, I will harm my own career in doi
n
g so, for I am under strict instruction to get this information without making a government matter of it. Please tell me, then, if there is some firm reason why you cannot discuss Gaia. Will you be arrested or otherwise punished, if you speak? Will you te
ll me plainly that I have no choice but to go to the ambassadorial height?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No no,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, who sounded utterly confused. \ldblquote I know nothing about government matters. We simply don\rquote t speak of that world.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Superstition?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \lquote Well, yes! Superstition! \endash Skies of Sayshell, in what way am I better than that foolish person who told you that Gaia was in hyperspace\endash or than my wife who won\rquote 
t even stay in a room where Gaia is mentioned and who may even have left the house for fear it will be smashed by\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Lightning?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote By some stroke from afar. And I, even I, hesitate to pronounce the name. Gaia! Gaia! The syllables do not hurt! I am unharmed! Yet I hesitate. \endash But please believe me when I say that I honestly don\rquote 
t know the co-ordinates for Gaia\rquote s star. I can try to help you get it, if that will help, but let me tell you that we don\rquote t discuss the world here in the Union. We keep hands and minds off it. I can tell you what little is known\endash 
really known, rather than supposed\endash and I doubt that you can learn anything more anywhere in these worlds of the Union.
\par \tab \ldblquote We know Gaia is an ancient world and there are some who think it is the oldest world in this sector of the Galaxy, but we are not certain. Patriotism tells us Sayshell Planet is the oldest; fear tells us Gaia Pl
anet is. The only way of combining the two is to suppose that Gaia is Earth, since it is known that Sayshell was settled by Earthpeople.
\par \tab \ldblquote Most historians think\endash among themselves\endash that Gaia Planet was founded i
ndependently. They think it is not a colony of any world of our Union and that the Union was not colonized by Gaia. There is no consensus on comparative age, whether Gaia was settled before or after Sayshell was.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote So far, what you know is nothing, since every possible alternative is believed by someone or other.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz nodded ruefully. \ldblquote It would seem so. It was comparatively late in our history that we became conscious of the existence of Gaia. We had been preoccupied at first in formi
ng the Union, then in fighting off the Galactic Empire, then in trying to find our proper role as an Imperial province and in limiting the power of the Viceroys.
\par \tab \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t till the days of Imperial weakness were far advanced that one of the later Viceroy
s, who was under very weak central control by then, came to realize that Gaia existed and seemed to maintain its independence from the Sayshellian province and even from the Empire itself. It simply kept to itself in isolation and secrecy, so that virtual
l
y nothing was known about it, anymore than is now known. The Viceroy decided to take it over. We have no details what happened, but his expedition was broken and few ships returned. In those days, of course, the ships were neither very good nor very well 
led.
\par \tab \ldblquote 
Sayshell itself rejoiced at the defeat of the Viceroy, who was considered an Imperial oppressor, and the debacle led almost directly to the re-establishment of our independence. The Sayshell Union snapped its ties with the Empire and we still celebra
te the anniversary of that event as Union Day. Almost out of gratitude we left Gaia alone for nearly a century, but the time came when we were strong enough to begin to think of a little imperialistic expansion of our own. Why not take over Gaia? Why not 
at least establish a Customs Union? We sent out a fleet and it was broken, too.
\par \tab \ldblquote Thereafter, we confined ourselves to an occasional attempt at trade\endash attempts that were invariably unsuccessful. Gaia remained in firm isolation and never\endash to anyone\rquote s knowledge\endash 
made the slightest attempt to trade or communicate with any other world. It certainly never made the slightest hostile move against anyone in any direction. And then\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz turned up the light by touching a control in the arm of his chair. In the light, Quintesetz\rquote s face took on a clearly sardonic expression. He went on, \ldblquote 
Since you are citizens of the Foundation, you perhaps remember the Mule.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize flushed. In five centuries of existence, the Foundation had been conquered only once. The conques
t had been only temporary and had not seriously interfered with its climb toward Second Empire, but surely no one who resented the Foundation and wished to puncture its self-satisfaction would fail to mention the Mule, its one conqueror. And it was likely
 (thought Trevize) that Quintesetz had raised the level of light in order that he might see Foundational self-satisfaction punctured.
\par \tab He said, \ldblquote Yes, we of the Foundation remember the Mule.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The Mule,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote ruled an Empire for a while, one th
at was as large as the Federation now controlled by the Foundation. He did not, however, rule us. He left us in peace. He passed through Sayshell at one time, however. We signed a declaration of neutrality and a statement of friendship. He asked nothing m
o
re. We were the only ones of whom he asked nothing more in the days before illness called a halt to his expansion and forced him to wait for death. He was not an unreasonable man, you know. He did not use unreasonable force, he was not bloody, and he rule
d humanely.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It was just that he was a conqueror,\rdblquote  said Trevize sarcastically.
\par \tab \ldblquote Like the Foundation,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz.
\par \tab Trevize, with no ready answer, said irritably, \ldblquote Do you have more to say about Gaia?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Just a statement that the Mule made. According to the account of the historic meeting between the Mule and President Kallo of the Union, the Mule is described as having put his signature to the document with a flourish and to have said, 
\ldblquote You are neutral even toward Gaia by this document, which is fortunate for you. Even I will not approach Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize shook his head. \ldblquote Why should he? Sayshell was eager to pledge neutrality and Gaia had no record of ever troubling anyone. The Mule was planning the conquest of the entire Galaxy at the time, so why dela
y for trifles? Time enough to turn on Sayshell and Gaia, when that was done.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Perhaps, perhaps,\rdblquote  said Quintesetz, \ldblquote but according to one witness at the time, a person we tend to believe, the Mule put down his pen as he said, \lquote Even I will not approach Gaia.\rquote 
 His voice then dropped and, in a whisper not meant to be heard, he added \lquote again.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Not meant to be heard, you say. Then how was it he was heard?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Because his pen rolled off the table when he put it down and a Sayshellian automatically approached and bent to pick it up. His ear was close to the Mule\rquote s mouth when the word \lquote again\rquote 
 was spoken and he heard it. He said nothing until after the Mule\rquote s death.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote How can you prove it was not an invention.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The man\rquote s life is not the kind that makes it probable he would invent something of this kind. His report is accepted.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And if it is?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The Mule was never in\endash or anywhere near\endash the Sayshell Union except on this one occasion, at least after he appeared on the Galactic scene. If he had ever been on Gaia, it had to be before he appeared on the Galactic scene.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well, where was the Mule born?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I don\rquote t think anyone knows,\rdblquote  said Trevize.
\par \tab \ldblquote In the Sayshell Union, there is a strong feeling he was born on Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Because of that one word?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Only partly. The Mule could not be defeated because he had strange mental powers. Gaia cannot be defeated either.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Gaia has not been defeated as yet. That does not necessarily prove it cannot be.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote 
Even the Mule would not approach. Search the records of his Overlordship. See if any region other than the Sayshell Union was so gingerly treated. And do you know that no one who has ever gone to Gaia for the purpose of peaceful trade has ever returned? W
hy do you suppose we know so little about it?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote Your attitude seems much like superstition.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Call it what you will. Since the time of the Mule, we have wiped Gaia out of our thinking. We don\rquote t want it to think of us. We only feel safe if we pretend it isn\rquote 
t there. It may be that the government has itself secretly initiated and encouraged the legend that Gaia has disappeared into hyperspace in the hope that people will forget that there is a real Star of that name.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You think that Gaia is a world of Mules, then?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It may be. I advise you, for your good, not to go there. If you do, you will never return. If the Foundation interferes with Gaia, it will show less intelligence than the Mule did. You might tell your ambassador that.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote Get me the co-ordinates and I will be off your world at once. I will reach Gaia and I will return.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Quintesetz said, \ldblquote I will get you the co-ordinates. The astronomy department works nights, of course, and I will get it for you now, if I can.\endash But let me suggest once more that you make no attempt to reach Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote I intend to make that attempt.\rdblquote 
\par \tab And Quintesetz said heavily, \ldblquote Then you intend suicide.\rdblquote 
