\par \tab JANOV PELORAT LOOKED OUT AT THE DIM LANDSCAPE IN THE GRAYING dawn with an odd mixture of regret and uncertainty.
\par \tab \ldblquote We aren\rquote t staying long enough, Golan. It seems a pleasant and interesting world. I would like to learn more about it.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize looked up from the computer with a wry smile. \ldblquote You don\rquote t think I would like to? We had three proper meals on the planet\endash totally different and each excellent. I\rquote 
d like more. And the only women we saw, we saw briefly\endash and some of them looked quite enticing, for\endash well, for what I\rquote ve got in mind.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat wrinkled his nose slightly. \ldblquote Oh, my dear chap. Those cowbells they call shoes, and all wrapped around in clashing colors, and whatever do they do to their eyelashes. Did you notice their eyelashes?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You might just as well believe I noticed everything, Janov. What you object to is superficial. They can easily be persuaded to wash their faces and, at the proper time, off come the shoes and the colors.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll take your word for that, Janov. However, I was thinking more of investigating the matter of Earth further. \lquote What we\rquote ve been told about Earth, thus far, is so unsatisfactory, so contradictory\endash 
radiation according to one person, robots according to another.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Death in either case.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote True,\rdblquote  said Pelorat reluctantly, \ldblquote but it may be that one is true and not the other,
 or that both are true to some extent, or that neither is true. Surely, Janov, when you hear tales that simply shroud matters in thickening mists of doubt, surely you must feel the itch to explore, to find out.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I do,\rdblquote  said Golan. \ldblquote By every dwarf star in
 the Galaxy, I do. The problem at hand, however, is Gaia. Once that is straightened out, we can go to Earth, or come back here to Sayshell for a more extended stay. But first, Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat nodded, \ldblquote The problem at hand! If we accept what Quintesetz told us, death is waiting for us on Gaia. Ought we to be going?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote I ask myself that. Are you afraid?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat hesitated as though he were probing his own feelings. Then he said in a quite simple and matter-of-fact manner. \ldblquote Yes. Terribly!\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize sat back in his chair and swiveled to face the other. He said, just as quietly and matter-of-factly, \ldblquote Janov, there\rquote s no reason for you to chance this. Say the word and I\rquote 
ll let you off on Sayshell with your personal belongings and with half our credits. I\rquote ll pick you up when I return and it will be on to Sirius Sector, if you wish, and Earth, if that\rquote s where it is. If I don\rquote 
t return, the Foundation people on Sayshell will see to it that you get back to Terminus. No hard feelings if you stay behind, old friend.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat\rquote s eyes blinked rapidly and his lips pressed together for a few moments. Then he said, rather huskily, \ldblquote Old friend? We\rquote ve known each other what? A week or so? Isn\rquote t it strange that I\rquote 
m going to refuse to leave the ship? I am afraid, but I want to remain with you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize moved his hands in a gesture of uncertainty. \ldblquote But why? I honestly don\rquote t ask it of you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I\rquote m not sure why, but I ask it of myself. It\rquote s\endash it\rquote s\endash Golan, I have faith in you. It seems to me you always know what you\rquote re doing. I wanted to go to Trantor where probably\endash as I now see
\endash nothing would have happened. You insisted on Gaia and Gaia must somehow be a raw nerve in the Galaxy. Things seem to happen in connection with it. And if that\rquote s not enough, Golan, I watched you force Quin
tesetz to give you the information about Gaia. That was such a skillful bluff. I was lost in admiration.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You have faith in me, then.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote Yes, I do.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize put his hand on the other\rquote s upper arm and seemed, for a moment, to be searching for words. Finally he said, \ldblquote Janov, will you forgive me in advance if my judgment is wrong, and if you in one way or another meet with\endash 
whatever unpleasant may be awaiting us?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote Oh, my dear fellow, why do you ask? I make the decision freely for my reasons, not yours. And, please\endash let us leave quickly. I don\rquote 
t trust my cowardice not to seize me by the throat and shame me for the rest of my life.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote As you say, Janov,\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote We\rquote ll leave at the earliest moment the computer will permit. This time, we\rquote ll be moving gravitically\endash straight up\endash 
as soon as we can be assured the atmosphere above is clear of other ships. And as the surrounding atmosphere grows less and less dense, we\rquote ll put on more and more speed. Well within the hour, we\rquote ll be in open space.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  Pelorat said and pinched the tip off a plastic coffee container. The opened orifice almost at once began steaming. Pelorat put the nipple to his mouth and sipped, allowing just enoug
h air to enter his mouth to cool the coffee to a bearable temperature.
\par \tab Trevize grinned. \ldblquote You\rquote ve learned how to use those things beautifully. You\rquote re a space veteran, Janov.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat stared at the plastic container for a moment and said, \ldblquote Now that we have ships that can adjust a gravitational field at will, surely we can use ordinary containers, can\rquote t we?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of course, but you\rquote re not going to get space people to give up their space-centered apparatus. How is a space rat going to put distance between himself
 and surface worms if he uses an openmouthed cup? See those rings on the walls and ceilings? Those have been traditional in spacecraft for twenty thousand years and more, but they\rquote re absolutely useless in a gravitic ship. Yet they\rquote 
re there and I\rquote ll bet the entire ship to a cup of coffee that your space rat will pretend he\rquote s being squashed into asphyxiation on takeoff and will then sway back and forth from those rings as though he\rquote 
s under zero-gray when its gee-one\endash normal-grav, that is\endash on both occasions.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You\rquote re joking.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Well, maybe a little, but there\rquote s always social inertia to everything\endash even technological advance. Those useless wall rings are there and the cups they supply us have nipples.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat nodded thoughtfully and continued to sip at his coffee. Finally he said, \ldblquote And when do we take off?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize laughed heartily and said, \ldblquote Got you. I began talking about wall rings and you never noticed that we were taking off right at that time. We\rquote re a mile high right now.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You don\rquote t mean it.\rdblquote 
