\par \tab IT TOOK HOURS FOR THE SHIP** FROM THE SPACE STATION TO REACH THE vicinity of the Far Star\endash very long hours for Trevize to endure.
\par \tab Had the situation been normal, Trevize would have tried to signal and would have expected a response. If there had been no response, he would have taken evasive action.
\par \tab Since he was unarmed and there had been no response, there was nothing to do but wait. The computer would not respond to any direction he could give it that involved anything outside the ship.
\par \tab Internally, at least, everything worked well. The life-support systems were in perfect order, so that he and Pelorat were physically comfortable. Somehow, that didn\rquote 
t help. Life dragged on and the uncertainty of what was to come was wearing him down. He noticed with irritation that Pelorat seemed calm. As though to make it worse, while Trevi
ze felt no sense of hunger at all, Pelorat opened a small container of chicken-bits, which on opening had rapidly and automatically warmed itself. Now he was eating it methodically.
\par \tab Trevize said irritably, \ldblquote Space, Janov! That stinks!\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat looked startled and sniffed at the container. \ldblquote It smells all right to me, Golan.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize shook his head. \ldblquote Don\rquote t mind me. I\rquote m just upset. But do use a fork. Your fingers will smell of chicken all day.\rdblquote 
