\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes. And the ground. And those trees. And that rabbit over there in the grass. And the man you can see through the trees. The whole planet and everything on it is Gaia. We\rquote re all individuals\endash we\rquote 
re all separate organisms\endash but we all share an overall consciousness. The inanimate planet does so least of all, the various forms of life to a varying degree, and human beings most of all\endash but we all share.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote I think, Trevize, that she means Gaia is some sort of group consciousness.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize nodded. \ldblquote I gathered that.\endash In that case, Bliss, who runs this world?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Bliss said, \ldblquote It runs itself. Those trees grow in rank and file of their own accord. They multiply only to the extent that is needed to replace those that for any reason die. Human beings harvest the apples that are needed; other anima
ls, including insects, eat their share\endash and only their share.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The insects know what their share is, do they?\rdblquote  said Trevize.
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes, they do\endash in a way. It rains when it is necessary and occasionally it rains rather hard when that is necessary\endash and occasionally there\rquote s a siege of dry weather when that is necessary.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And the rain knows what to do, does it?\rdblquote 
