\par \tab \ldblquote In a way,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote it is a brief biography of myself. It tells the hearer\endash or reader, or senser\endash 
who I am, what part I have played in the whole, what I have accomplished. For fifty years and more, however, I have been satisfied to be referred to as Dom. When there are other Doms at issue, I can be called Domandio\endash 
and in my various professional relationships other variants are used. Once a Gaian year \endash on my birthday\endash my full name is recited-in-mind, as I have just recited it for you in voice. It is very effective, but it is personally embarrassing.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab He was tall and thin\endash almost to the point of emaciation. His deep-set eyes sparkled with anomalous youth, though he moved rather slowly. His jutting nose was thin and long and flared at the nostrils. His hands, prominently veined though t
hey were, showed no signs of arthritic disability. He wore a long robe that was as gray as his hair. It descended to his ankles and his sandals left his toes bare.
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote How old are you, sir?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote 
Please address me as Dom, Trev. To use other modes of address induces formality and inhibits the free exchange of ideas between you and me. In Galactic Standard Years, I am just past ninety-three, but the real celebration will come not very many months fr
om now, when I reach the ninetieth anniversary of my birth in Gaian years.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I would not have guessed you at more than seventy-five, s\endash Dom,\rdblquote  said Trevize.
\par \tab \ldblquote By Gaian standards I am not remarkable, either in years or in appearance of years, Trev.\endash But come, have we eaten?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat looked down at his plate, on which perceptible remnants of a most unremarkable and indifferently prepared meal remained, and said in a diffident manner, \ldblquote Dom, may I attempt to ask an embarrassing question? Of course, if it\rquote 
s offensive, you will please say so, and I will withdraw it.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Go ahead,\rdblquote  said Dom, smiling. \ldblquote I am anxious to explain to you anything about Gaia which arouses your curiosity.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  said Trevize at once.
\par \tab \ldblquote Because you are honored guests\endash May I have Pel\rquote s question?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote Since all things on Gaia share in the group consciousness, how is it that you\endash one element of the group\endash can eat this, which was clearly another element?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote True! But all things recycle. We must eat and everything we can eat, plant as well as animal\endash even the inanimate seasonings\endash 
are part of Gaia. But, then, you see, nothing is killed for pleasure or sport, nothing is killed with unnecessary pain. And I\rquote m afraid we make no attempt to glorify our meal preparations, for no Gaian would eat exc
ept that one must. You did not enjoy this meal, Pel? Trev? Well, meals are not to enjoy.
\par \tab \ldblquote Then, too, what is eaten remains, after all, part of the planetary consciousness. Insofar as portions of it are incorporated into my body, it will participate in a larger share of the total consciousness. When I die, I, too, will be eaten
\endash even if only by decay bacteria\endash and I will then participate in a far smaller share of the total. But someday, parts of me will be parts of other human beings, parts of many.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote A sort of transmigration of souls.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Of what, Pel?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I speak of an old myth that is current on some worlds.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Ah, I don\rquote t know of it. You must tell me on some occasion.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote But your individual consciousness\endash whatever it is about you that is Dom\endash will never fully reassemble.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No, of course not. But does that matter? I will still be part of Gaia and that is what counts. There are mystics among us who wonder if we should take measures to develop group memories of past existences, but th
e sense-of-Gaia is that this cannot be done in any practical way and would serve no useful purpose. It would merely blur present consciousness. \endash 
Of course, as conditions change, the sense-of-Gaia may change, too, but I find no chance of that in the foreseeable future.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why must you die, Dom?\rdblquote  asked Trevize. \ldblquote Look at you in your nineties. Could not the group consciousness\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab For the first time, Dom frowned. \ldblquote Never,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I can contribute only so much. Each new individual is a reshuffling of molecules 
and genes into something new. New talents, new abilities, new contributions to Gaia. We must have them\endash 
and the only way we can is to make room. I have done more than most, but even I have my limit and it is approaching. There is no more desire to live past one\rquote s time than to die before it.\rdblquote 
\par \tab And then, as if realizing he had lent a suddenly somber note to the evening, he rose and stretched his arms out to the two. \ldblquote Come, Trev\endash Pel\endash let us move into my studio where I can show you some of my personal art objects
. You won\rquote t blame an old man for his little vanities, I hope.\rdblquote 
\par \tab He led the way into another room where, on a small circular table, there were a group of smoky lenses connected in pairs.
\par \tab \ldblquote These,\rdblquote  said Dom, \ldblquote are Participations I have designed. I am not one of the masters, but I specialize in inanimates, which few of the masters bother with.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote May I pick one up? Are they fragile?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No no. Bounce them on the floor if you like.\endash Or perhaps you had better not. Concussion could dull the sharpness of the vision.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote How are they used, Dom?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You put them over your eyes. They\rquote ll cling. They do not transmit light. Quite the contrary. They obscure light that might otherwise distract you\endash though the sensations do reach your brain by way of the optic nerve
. Essentially your consciousness is sharpened and is allowed to participate in other facets of Gaia. In other words, if you look at that wall, you will experience that wall as it appears to itself.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Fascinating,\rdblquote  muttered Pelorat. \ldblquote may I try that?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Certainly, Pel. You may take one at random. Each is a different construct that shows the wall\endash or any other inanimate object you look at\endash in a different aspect of the object\rquote s consciousness.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat placed one pair over his eyes and they clung there at once. He started at the touch and then remained motionless for a long time.
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote When you are through, place your hands on either side of the Participation and press them toward each other. It will come right off.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat did so, blinked his eyes rapidly, then rubbed them.
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote What did you experience?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote It\rquote s hard to describe. The wall seemed to twinkle and glisten and, at times, it seemed to turn fluid. It seemed to have ribs and changing symmetries. I\endash I\rquote m sorry, Dom, but I did not find it attractive.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom sighed. \ldblquote You do not participate in Gaia, so you would not see what we see. I had rather feared that. Too bad! I assure you that although these Participations are enjoyed primarily for their 
aesthetic value, they have their practical uses, too. A happy wall is a long-lived wall, a practical wall, a useful wall.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote A happy wall?\rdblquote  said Trevize, smiling slightly.
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote There is a dim sensation that a wall experiences that is analogous to what \lquote happy\rquote 
 means to us. A wall is happy when it is well designed, when it rests firmly on its foundation, when its symmetry balances its parts and produces no unpleasant stresses. Good design can be worked out on the mathematical principles of mechanics, b
ut the use of a proper Participation can fine tune it down to virtually atomic dimensions. No sculptor can possibly produce a first-class work of art here on Gaia without a well-crafted Participation and the ones I produce of this particular type are cons
idered excellent\endash if I do say so myself.
\par \tab \ldblquote Animate Participations, which are not my field,\rdblquote  and Dom was going on with the kind of excitement one expects in someone riding his hobby, \ldblquote give us, by analogy, a direct experience of ecological balance. The ecologi
cal balance on Gaia is rather simple, as it is on all worlds, but here, at least, we have the hope of making it more complex and thus enriching the total consciousness enormously.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize held up his hand in order to forestall Pelorat and wave him into silence. He said, \ldblquote How do you know that a planet can bear a more complex ecological balance if they all have simple ones?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Dom, his eyes twinkling shrewdly, \ldblquote you are testing the old man. You know as well as I do that the original home of humanity, Earth, had an enormously complex ecological balance. It is only the secondary worlds
\endash the derived worlds\endash that are simple.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat would not be kept silent. \ldblquote But that is the problem I have set myself in life. Why was it only Earth that bore a complex ecology? What distinguished it from other worlds? Why did millions upon millions of other worlds in the Galaxy
\endash worlds that were capable of bearing life\endash develop only an undistinguished vegetation, together with small and unintelligent animal life-forms?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote We have a tale about that\endash a fable, perhaps. I cannot vouch for its authenticity. In fact, on the face of it, it sounds like fiction.\rdblquote 
\par \tab It was at this point that Bliss\endash who had not participated in the meal\endash entered, smiling at Pelorat. She was wearing a silvery blouse, very sheer.
\par \tab Pelorat rose at once. \ldblquote I thought you had left us.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Not at all. I had reports to make out, work to do. May I join you now, Dom?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom had also risen (though Trevize remained seated). \ldblquote You are entirely welcome and you ravish these aged eyes.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It is for your ravishment that I put on this blouse. Pel is above such things and Trev dislikes them.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote If you think I am above such things, Bliss, I may surprise you someday.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What a delightful surprise that would be,\rdblquote  Bliss said, and sat down. The two men did as well. \ldblquote Please don\rquote t let me interrupt you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote I was about to tell our guests the story of Eternity.\endash To understand it, you must first understand that there are many different Universes that can exist\endash v
irtually an infinite number. Every single event that takes place can take place or not take place, or can take place in this fashion or in that fashion, and each of an enormous number of alternatives will result in a future course of events that are disti
nct to at least some degree.
\par \tab \ldblquote Bliss might not have come in just now; or she might have been with us a little earlier; or much earlier; or having come in now, she might have worn a different blouse; or even in this blouse, she might not have smiled roguishl
y at elderly men as is her kindhearted custom. In each of these alternatives\endash or in each of a very large number of other alternatives of this one event\endash 
the Universe would have taken a different track thereafter, and so on for every other variation of every other event, however minor.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize stirred restlessly. \ldblquote I believe this is a common speculation in quantum mechanics\endash a very ancient one, in fact.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Ah, you\rquote ve heard of it. But let us go on. Imagine it is possible for human beings to freeze all the infinite number of Universes, to step from one to another at will, and to choose which one should be made \lquote real\rquote 
\endash whatever that word means in this connection.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote I hear your words and can even imagine the concept you describe, but I cannot make myself believe that anything like this could ever happen.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Nor I, on the whole,\rdblquote  said Dom, \ldblquote which is why I say that it would all seem to be a fable. Nevertheless, the fable states that there were those who could step out of time and examine the endless stra
nds of potential reality. These people were called the Eternals and when they were out of time they were said to be in Eternity.
\par \tab \ldblquote It was their task to choose a Reality that would be most suitable to humanity. They modified endlessly\endash and the story goes int
o great detail, for I must tell you that it has been written in the form of an epic of inordinate length. Eventually they found (so it is said) a Universe in which Earth was the only planet in the entire Galaxy on which could be found a complex ecological
 system, together with the development of an intelligent species capable of working out a high technology.
\par \tab \ldblquote That, they decided, was the situation in which humanity could be most secure. They froze that strand of events as Reality and then ceased operations
. Now we live in a Galaxy that has been settled by human beings only, and, to a large extent, by the plants, animals, and microscopic life that they carry with them\endash voluntarily or  inadvertently\endash 
from planet to planet and which usually overwhelm the indigenous life.
\par \tab \ldblquote 
Somewhere in the dim mists of probability there are other Realities in which the Galaxy is host to many intelligences, but they are unreachable. We in our Reality are alone. From every action and every event in our Reality, there are new branch
es that set off, with only one in each separate case being a continuation of Reality, so that there are vast numbers of potential Universes\endash perhaps an infinite number\endash 
stemming from ours, but all of them are presumably alike in containing the one-intelligence Galaxy in which we live.\endash 
Or perhaps I should say that all but a vanishingly small percentage are alike in this way, for it is dangerous to rule out anything where the possibilities approach the infinite.\rdblquote 
\par \tab He stopped, shrugged slightly, and added, \ldblquote At least, that\rquote s the story. It dates back to before the founding of Gaia. I don\rquote t vouch for its truth.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The three others had listened intently. Bliss nodded her head, as though it were something she had heard before and she were checking the accuracy of Dom\rquote s account.
\par \tab Pelorat reacted with a silent solemnity for the better part of a minute and then balled his fist and brought it down upon the arm of his chair.
\par \tab \ldblquote No,\rdblquote  he said is a strangled tone, \ldblquote that affects nothing. There\rquote s no way of demonstrating the truth of the story by observation or by reason, so it can\rquote 
t ever be anything but a piece of speculation, but aside from that\endash Suppose it\rquote s true! The Universe we live in is still one in which only Earth has developed a rich life and an intelligent species, so that in this Universe\endash 
whether it is the all-in-all or only one out of an infinite number of possibilities\endash there must be something unique in the nature of the planet Earth. We should still want to know what that uniqueness is.\rdblquote 
\par \tab In the silence that followed, it was Trevize who finally stirred and shook his head.
\par \tab \ldblquote No, Janov,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote that\rquote s not the way it works. Let us say that the chances are one in a billion trillion\endash one in 10}{\f1\lang2057\super\cgrid0 21}{\f1\lang2057\cgrid0 \endash 
that out of the billion of habitable planets in the Galaxy only Earth\endash  through the workings of sheer chance\endash would happen to develop a rich ecology and, eventually, intelligence. If that is so, then one in 10}{\f1\lang2057\super\cgrid0 21}{
\f1\lang2057\cgrid0  of the various strands of potential Realities would represent such a Galaxy and the Eternals picked it. We live, therefore, i
n a Universe in which Earth is the only planet to develop a complex ecology, an intelligent species, a high technology\endash not because there is something special about Earth, but because simply by chance it developed on Earth and nowhere else.
\par \tab \ldblquote I suppose, in fact,\rdblquote  Trevize went on thoughtfully, \ldblquote 
that there are strands of Reality in which only Gaia has developed an intelligent species, or only Sayshell, or only Terminus, or only some planet which in this Reality happens to bear no life at all. And all of these 
very special cases are a vanishingly small percentage of the total number of Realities in which there is more than one intelligent species in the Galaxy.\endash 
I suppose that if the Eternals had looked long enough they would have found a potential strand of Reality in which every single habitable planet had developed an intelligent species.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote Might you not also argue that a Reality had been found in which Earth was for some reason not as it was in other strands, but specially suited in some way for
 the development of intelligence? In fact, you can go further and say that a Reality had been found in which the whole Galaxy was not as it was in other strands, but was somehow in such a state of development that only Earth could produce intelligence.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote You might argue so, but I would suppose that my version makes more sense.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote That\rquote s a purely subjective decision, of course\endash \rdblquote  began Pelorat with some heat, but Dom interrupted, saying \ldblquote This is logic-chopping. Come, let us not spoil what is pr
oving, at least for me, a pleasant and leisurely evening.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat endeavored to relax and to allow his heat to drain away. He smiled finally and said, \ldblquote As you say, Dom.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize, who had been casting glances at Bliss, who sat with mocking demurity, hands in her lap, now said, \ldblquote And how did this world come to be, Dom? Gaia, with its group consciousness?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom\rquote s old head leaned back and he laughed in a high-pitched manner. His face crinkled as he said, \ldblquote Fables again! I think about that sometimes, when I rea
d what records we have on human history. No matter how carefully records are kept and filed and computerized, they grow fuzzy with time. Stories grow by accretion. Tales accumulate\endash like dust. The longer the time lapse, the dustier the history
\endash until it degenerates into fables.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote We historians are familiar with the process, Dom. There is a certain preference for the fable. \lquote The falsely dramatic drives out the truly dull,\rquote  said Liebel Gennerat about fifteen centuries ago. It\rquote 
s called Gennerat\rquote s Law now.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Is it?\rdblquote  said Dom. \ldblquote And I thought the notion was a cynical invention of my own. Well, Gennerat\rquote s Law fills our past history with glamour and uncertainty.\endash Do you know what a robot is?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote We found out on Sayshell,\rdblquote  said Trevize dryly.
\par \tab \ldblquote You saw one?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No. We were asked the question and, when we answered in the negative, it was explained to us.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I understand.\endash Humanity once lived with robots, you know, but it didn\rquote t work well.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote So we were told.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The robots were deeply indoctrinated with what are called the Three Laws of Robotics, which date back into prehistory. There are several versions of what those Three Laws might have been. The orthodox view has the following reading: 
\lquote 1) A robot may not harm a human being or, through inaction, allow a hu
man being to come to harm; 2) A robot must obey the orders given it by human beings, except where such orders would conflict with the First Law; 3) A robot must protect its own existence, as long as such protection does not conflict with the First or Seco
nd Law.\rquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote 
As robots grew more intelligent and versatile, they interpreted these Laws, especially the all-overriding First, more and more generously and assumed, to a greater and greater degree, the role of protector of humanity. The protection stifled peop
le and grew unbearable.
\par \tab \ldblquote The robots were entirely kind. Their labors were clearly humane and were meant entirely for the benefit of all\endash which somehow made them all the more unbearable.
\par \tab \ldblquote Every robotic advance made the situation worse. Robots were developed with telepathic capacity, but that meant that even human thought could be monitored, so that human behavior became still more dependent on robotic oversight.
\par \tab \ldblquote Again robots grew steadily more like human beings in appearance, but they were unmistakably robots in behavior and being humanoid made them more repulsive. So, of course, it had to come to an end.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Why \lquote of course\rquote ?\rdblquote  asked Pelorat, who had been listening intently.
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote It\rquote s a matter of following the logic to the bitter end. Eventually the r
obots grew advanced enough to become just sufficiently human to appreciate why human beings should resent being deprived of everything human in the name of their own good. In the long run, the robots were forced to decide that humanity might be better off
 caring for themselves, however carelessly and ineffectively.
\par \tab \ldblquote Therefore, it is said, it was the robots who established Eternity somehow and became the Eternals. They located a Reality in which they felt that human beings could be as secure as possible\endash alo
ne in the Galaxy. Then, having done what they could to guard us and in order to fulfill the First Law in the truest sense, the robots of their own accord ceased to function and ever since we have been human beings\endash advancing, however we can, alone.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom paused. He looked from Trevize to Pelorat, and then said, \ldblquote Well, do you believe all that?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize shook his head slowly. \ldblquote No. There is nothing like this in any historical record I have ever heard of. How about you, Janov?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote There are myths that are similar in some ways.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Come, Janov, there are myths that would match anything that any of us can make up, given sufficiently ingenious interpretation. I\rquote m talking about history\endash reliable records.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Oh well. Nothing there, as far as I know.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote I\rquote 
m not surprised. Before the robots withdrew, many parties of human beings left to colonize robotless worlds in deeper space, in order to take their own measures for freedom. They came particularly from overcrowded Earth, with its 
long history of resistance to robots. The new worlds were founded fresh and they did not even want to remember their bitter humiliation as children under robot nursemaids. They kept no records of it and they forgot.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote This is unlikely.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat turned to him. \ldblquote No, Golan. It\rquote 
s not at all unlikely. Societies create their own history and tend to wipe out lowly beginnings, either by forgetting them or inventing totally fictitious heroic rescues. The Imperial government made attempts to suppress 
knowledge of the pre-Imperial past in order to strengthen the mystic aura of eternal rule. Then, too, there are almost no records of the days before hyperspatial travel\endash and you know that the very existence of Earth is unknown to most people today.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote You can\rquote t have it both ways, Janov. If the Galaxy has forgotten the robots, how is it that Gaia remembers?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Bliss intervened with a sudden lilt of soprano laughter. \ldblquote We\rquote re different.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes?\rdblquote  said Trevize. \ldblquote In what way?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote Now, Bliss, l
eave this to me. We are different, men of Terminus. Of all the refugee groups fleeing from robotic domination, we who eventually reached Gaia (following in the track of others who reached Sayshell) were the only ones who had learned the craft of telepathy
 from the robots.
\par \tab \ldblquote it is a craft, you know. It is inherent in the human mind, but it must be developed in a very subtle and difficult manner. It takes many generations to reach its full potential, but once well begun, it feeds on itself. We have been at it
 for over twenty thousand years and the sense-of-Gaia is that full potential has even now not been reached. It was long ago that our development of telepathy made us aware of group consciousness\endash 
first only of human beings; then animals; then plants; and finally, not many centuries ago, the inanimate structure of the planet itself.
\par \tab \ldblquote Because we traced this back to the robots, we did not forget them. We considered them not our nursemaids but our teachers. We felt they had opened our mind to something we would
 never for one moment want them closed to. We remember them with gratitude.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote But just as once you were children to the robots, now you are children to the group consciousness. Have you not lost humanity now, as you had then?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It is different, Trev. What we do now is our own choice\endash 
our own choice. That is what counts. It is not forced on us from outside, but is developed from the inside. It is something we never forget. And we are different in another way, too. We are unique in the Galaxy. There is no world like Gaia.\rdblquote 

\par \tab \ldblquote How can you be sure?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote We would know, Trev. We would detect a world consciousness such as ours even at the other end of the Galaxy. We can detect the beginnings of such a consciousness in your Second Foundation, for instance, though not until two centuries ago.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote At the time of the Mule?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes. One of ours.\rdblquote  Dom looked grim. \ldblquote He was an aberrant and he left us. We were na\'efve enough to think that was not possible, so we did not act in time to stop him. Then, when we turned o
ur attention to the Outside Worlds, we became aware of what you call the Second Foundation and we left it to them.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize stared blankly for several moments, then muttered, \ldblquote There go our history books!\rdblquote  He shook his head and said in a louder tone of voice, \ldblquote That was rather cowardly of Gaia, wasn\rquote t it, to do so?\rdblquote 
 said Trevize. \ldblquote He was your responsibility.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote You are right. But once we finally turned our eyes upon the Galaxy, we saw what until then we had been blind to, so that the tragedy of the Mule prov
ed a life-saving matter to us. It was then that we recognized that eventually a dangerous crisis would come upon us. And it has\endash but not before we were able to take measures, thanks to the incident of the Mule.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What sort of crisis?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote One that threatens us with destruction?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I can\rquote t believe that. You held off the Empire, the Mule, and Sayshell. You have a group consciousness that can pluck a ship out of space at a distance of millions of kilometers. What can you have to fear?\endash 
Look at Bliss. She doesn\rquote t look the least bit perturbed. She doesn\rquote t think there\rquote s a crisis.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Bliss had placed one shapely leg over the arm of the chair and wriggled her toes at him. \ldblquote Of course I\rquote m not worried, Trev. You\rquote ll handle it.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trev said forcefully, \ldblquote Me?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote Gaia has brought you here by means of a hundred gentle manipulations. It is you who must face our crisis.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trev stared at him and slowly his face turned from stupefaction into gathering rage. \ldblquote Me? Why, in all of space, me? I have nothing to do with this.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Nevertheless, Trev,\rdblquote  said Dom with an almost hypnotic calmness, \ldblquote you. Only you. In all of space, only you.\rdblquote 
