r yourself that by First Law I could never abandon him, unless he ordered me to do so and I were, in addition, convinced that he meant it and that I would be hurting him more by staying than by leaving.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Would not a younger man\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote What younger man? You are a younger man, but I do not conceive you as needing me in the same sense that Pel does, and, in fact, you do not want me, so that the First Law would prevent me from attempting to cling to you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Not me. Another younger man\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote There is no other. Who is there on Gaia other than Pel and yourself that would qualify as human beings in the non-Gaian sense?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, more softly, \ldblquote And if you are not a robot?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Make up your mind,\rdblquote  said Bliss.
\par \tab \ldblquote I say, if you are not a robot?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Then I say that, in that case, you have no right to say anything at all. It is for myself and for Pel to decide.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trev said, \ldblquote Then I return to my first point. I want my reward and that reward is that you will treat him well. I won\rquote t press the point of your identity. Simply assure me, as one intelligence to another, that you will treat him well.
\rdblquote 
\par \tab And Bliss said softly, \ldblquote I will treat him well\endash not as a reward to you, but because I wish to. It is my earnest desire. I will treat him well.\rdblquote  She called \ldblquote Pel!\rdblquote  And again, \ldblquote Pel!\rdblquote 

\par \tab Pelorat entered from outside, \ldblquote Yes, Bliss.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Bliss held out her hand to him. \ldblquote I think Trev wants to say something.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat took her hand and Trevize then took the doubled hand in his two. \ldblquote Janov,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I am happy for both of you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Pelorat said, \ldblquote Oh, my dear fellow.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote I will probably be leaving Gaia. I go now to speak to Dom about that. I don\rquote t know when or if we will meet again, Janov, but, in any case, we did well together.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote We did well,\rdblquote  said Pelorat, smiling.
\par \tab \ldblquote Good-bye, Bliss, and, in advance, thank you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Good-bye, Trev.\rdblquote 
\par \tab And Trevize, with a wave of his hand, left the house.
\par **
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote You did well, Trev.\endash But then, you did as I thought you would.\rdblquote 
\par \tab They were once more sitting over a meal, as unsatisfactory as the first had been, but Trevize did not mind. He might not be eating on Gaia again.
\par \tab He said, \ldblquote I did as I thought you would, but not, perhaps, for the reason you thought I would.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Surely you were sure of the correctness of your decision.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes, I was, but not because of any mystic grip I have on certainty. If I chose Galaxia, it was through ordinary reasoning\endash 
the sort of reasoning that anyone else might have used to come to a decision. Would you care to have me explain?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I most certainly would, Trev.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote There were three things I might have done. I might have joined the First Foundation, or joined the Second Foundation, or joined Gaia.
\par \tab \ldblquote If I had joined the First Foundation, Mayor Branno would have taken immediate action to establish d
omination over the Second Foundation and over Gaia. If I had joined the Second Foundation, Speaker Gendibal would have taken immediate action to establish domination over the First Foundation and over Gaia. In either case, what would have taken place woul
d have been irreversible\endash and if either were the wrong solution, it would have been irreversibly catastrophic.
\par \tab \ldblquote If I joined with Gaia, however, then the First Foundation and the Second Foundation would each have been left with the conviction of having won a
 relatively minor victory. All would then have continued as before, since the building of Galaxia, I had already been told, would take generations, even centuries.
\par \tab \ldblquote Joining with Gaia was my way of temporizing, then, and of making sure that there would remain time to modify matters\endash or even reverse them\endash if my decision were wrong.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom raised his eyebrows. His old, almost cadaverous face remained otherwise expressionless. He said in his piping voice, \ldblquote And is it your opinion that your decision may turn out wrong?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize shrugged. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think so, but there is one thing I must do in order that I might know. It is my intention to visit Earth, if I can find that world.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote We will certainly not stop you if you wish to leave us, Trev\endash \rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I do not fit on your world.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote No more than Pel does, yet you are as welcome to remain as he is. Still, we will not hold you.\endash But tell me, why do you wish to visit Earth?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize said, \ldblquote I rather think you understand.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I do not.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote There is a piece of information you withheld from me, Dom. Perhaps you had your reasons, but I wish you had not.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom said, \ldblquote I do not follow you.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Look, Dom, in order to make my decision, I used my computer and for a brief moment I found myself in touch with the minds of those about me\endash Mayor Bra
nno, Speaker Gendibal, Novi. I caught glimpses of a number of matters that, in isolation, meant little to me, as, for example, the various effects Gaia, through Novi, had produced on Trantor\endash 
effects that were intended to maneuver the Speaker into going to Gaia.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Yes?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote And one of those things was the clearing from Trantor\rquote s library of all references to Earth.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote The clearing of references to Earth?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Exactly. So Earth must be important\endash 
and not only does it appear that the Second Foundation must know nothing about it, but that I must not, either. And if I am to take the responsibility for the direction of Galactic development, I do not willingly accept ignorance. Would you consider telli
ng me why it was so important to keep knowledge of Earth hidden?\rdblquote 
\par \tab Dom said solemnly, \ldblquote Trev, Gaia knows nothing about such clearance. Nothing!\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Are you telling me that Gaia is not responsible?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote It is not responsible.\rdblquote 
\par \tab Trevize thought for a while, the tip of his tongue moving slowly and meditatively over his lips. \ldblquote Who was responsible, then?\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote I don\rquote t know. I can see no purpose in it.\rdblquote 
\par \tab The two men stared at each other and then Dom said, \ldblquote You are right. We had seemed to have reached a most satisfactory conclusion, but while this point remains unsettled, we dare not rest. \endash 
Stay a while with us and let us see what we can reason out. Then you can leave, with our full help.\rdblquote 
\par \tab \ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said Trevize.
